column12: Perfectionnement à l'évaluation de trajectoires de cibles.
column13: L'invention concerne un procédé et un appareil qui déterminent si une cible nouvellement signalée peut être corrélée à des trajectoires de cibles déjà mémorisées dans une base de données. La corrélation est réalisée par étapes avec rejet de trajectoires de cibles mémorisées qui ne peuvent pas être corrélées et acceptation de trajectoires de cibles étroitement corrélées, et comporte un dispositif d'application d'une décision (16c) destiné à accepter une trajectoire de cible mémorisée comme trajectoire corrélée uniquement dans des conditions sévères.

column12: ENFORCING POLICIES IN WIRELESS COMMUNICATION USING EXCHANGED IDENTITIES
column13: Techniques for facilitating the exchange of information and transactions between two entities associated with two wireless devices when the devices are in close proximity to each other. A first device uses a first short range wireless capability to detect an identifier transmitted from a second device in proximity, ideally using existing radio capabilities such as Bluetooth (IEEE802.15.1-2002) or Wi-Fi (IEEE802.11). The detected identifier, being associated with the device, is also associated with an entity. Rather than directly exchanging application data flow between the two devices using the short range wireless capability, a second wireless capability allows for one or more of the devices to communicate with a central server via the internet, and perform the exchange of application data flow. By using a central server to draw on stored information and content associated with the entities the server can broker the exchange of information between the entities and the devices.

column12: Exchanging identifiers between wireless communication to determine further information to be exchanged or further services to be provided
column13: A server exchanges information between one or more wireless devices to complete a transaction. The server receives second device identifier information from a first wireless device using a wide area network. The second device identifier information was previously provided to the first wireless device using short range wireless communication. The server then uses the second device identifier information to determine additional information concerning an entity or object located in proximity to the second device, and then the server delivers information to the first wireless device based at least in part upon both (a) the second device identifier and (b) a current step in a multiple step process for an ongoing electronic commerce transaction.

column12: Enforcing policies in wireless communication using exchanged identities
column13: Techniques for facilitating the exchange of information and transactions between two entities associated with two wireless devices when the devices are in close proximity to each other. A first device uses a first short range wireless capability to detect an identifier transmitted from a second device in proximity, ideally using existing radio capabilities such as Bluetooth (IEEE802.15.1-2002) or Wi-Fi (IEEE802.11). The detected identifier, being associated with the device, is also associated with an entity. Rather than directly exchanging application data flow between the two devices using the short range wireless capability, a second wireless capability allows for one or more of the devices to communicate with a central server via the internet, and perform the exchange of application data flow. By using a central server to draw on stored information and content associated with the entities the server can broker the exchange of information between the entities and the devices.

column12: EXCHANGING IDENTIFIERS BETWEEN WIRELESS COMMUNICATION TO DETERMINE FURTHER INFORMATION TO BE EXCHANGED OR FURTHER SERVICES TO BE PROVIDED
column13: A server exchanges information between one or more wireless devices to complete a transaction. The server receives second device identifier information from a first wireless device using a wide area network. The second device identifier information was previously provided to the first wireless device using short range wireless communication. The server then uses the second device identifier information to determine additional information concerning an entity or object located in proximity to the second device, and then the server delivers information to the first wireless device based at least in part upon both (a) the second device identifier and (b) a current step in a multiple step process for an ongoing electronic commerce transaction.

column13: This invention describes a buoyancy aid that is pre-formed from a buoyant foam plastic material and has an pre-formed internal tube that is sealed. The internal tube and the pre-formed buoyant foam are all shaped to provide support for a users head, and is designed to keep the users head above water. The buoyancy aid has an external covering that is selected to prevent chafing the user, as well as being water and mold resistant. The buoyancy aid is so designed as to be comfortable to the user, and enhance the wearers use of the buoyancy aid.

column12: EXCHANGING IDENTIFIERS BETWEEN WIRELESS COMMUNICATION TO DETERMINE FURTHER INFORMATION TO BE EXCHANGED OR FURTHER SERVICES TO BE PROVIDED
column13: A server exchanges information between one or more wireless devices to complete a transaction. The server receives second device identifier information from a first wireless device using a wide area network. The second device identifier information was previously provided to the first wireless device using short range wireless communication. The server then uses the second device identifier information to determine additional information concerning an entity or object located in proximity to the second device, and then the server delivers information to the first wireless device based at least in part upon both (a) the second device identifier and (b) a current step in a multiple step process for an ongoing electronic commerce transaction.
column15: PROCTOR JR JAMES ARTHUR;;PROCTOR III JAMES ARTHUR

column12: Visual identification information used as confirmation in a wireless communication
column13: Techniques for facilitating the exchange of information and transactions between two entities associated with two wireless devices when the devices are in close proximity to each other. A first device uses a first short range wireless capability to detect an identifier transmitted from a second device in proximity, ideally using existing radio capabilities such as Bluetooth (IEEE802.15.1-2002) or Wi-Fi (IEEE802.11). The detected identifier, being associated with the device, is also associated with an entity. Rather than directly exchanging application data flow between the two devices using the short range wireless capability, a second wireless capability allows for one or more of the devices to communicate with a central server via the internet, and perform the exchange of application data flow. By using a central server to draw on stored information and content associated with the entities the server can broker the exchange of information between the entities and the devices.

column13: This invention describes a buoyancy aid that is pre-formed from a buoyant foam plastic material and has an pre-formed internal tube that is sealed. The internal tube and the pre-formed buoyant foam are all shaped to provide support for a users head, and is designed to keep the users head above water. The buoyancy aid has an external covering that is selected to prevent chafing the user, as well as being water and mold resistant. The buoyancy aid is so designed as to be comfortable to the user, and enhance the wearers use of the buoyancy aid.

Fluid controlled tension winding and unwinding device
column13: 918,937. Variable-speed gear. HOBBS MANUFACTURING CO. March 7, 1961, No. 8278/61. Class 80 (2). [Also in Groups IX, XVI and XXXIV] A variable-speed gear for use with wire, paper &c. winding and unwinding apparatus comprises a driving shaft 17 fast on which is a carrier supporting a bevel planet pinion 20 meshing a reaction side gear 23 driving through a train 22, 27 to a pump 26 which forces liquid through an adjustable orifice 69, and also meshing a side gear 25 driving through a train 24, 31 to a driven shaft 29. A simple reverse gear 39, 45, 44; 36, 46 between the driven shaft 29 and a layshaft 42 is manually controlled by means of a knob 52 and links &c. sliding a positive clutch collar 32 on the layshaft to rotate the latter always in the same direction, independently of reversal of the direction of rotation of the driving shaft 17 for winding and unwinding operations. The layshaft 42 drives through a train 46, 63 to the side gear 62 of a second differential having its planet pinion 61 driven by an electric motor 59, the second side gear 64 of this differential driving an auxiliary pump 67 supplying liquid through a pipe 73 to a cylinder 68 containing a free floating piston 70. The pump 26 supplies liquid through a pipe 28 to the opposite side of the free floating piston 70 from a sump 14, whence it returns through the orifice 69, partially closed by the piston. When the driving shaft 17 is rotated in one direction for winding, decreasing speed of the driven shaft 29 causes the pump 26 to supply more liquid to the cylinder 68 and thereby tend to slide the piston 70 rightwards of Fig. 2, this action being opposed by the change in speed of rotation of the auxiliary pump 67 which works harder and supplies a higher pressure to the opposite side of the piston, so that the latter remains in the same position and maintains a constant size of the orifice 69, whereby the material is wound at a constant tension. When the driving shaft 17 is rotated in the opposite direction for unwinding, and following change-over of the reverse gear 32 &c., increasing speed of the driven shaft 29 causes the auxiliary pump 67 to slow down, thus allowing the free floating piston 70 to move to the right of Fig. 2 and increase the size of the orifice 69 through which the pump 26 is forcing liquid, reducing the torque applied to the driven shaft. The tension in the wound material can be adjusted by a needle valve 75 through which liquid supplied from the auxiliary pump 67 returns to the sump 14. The electric motor 59 may have its speed of rotation controlled by the operations of the main process machine containing the gear, to vary the speed of rotation of the driven shaft 29. The sump 14 is formed in the upper part of a casing 10 containing the gearing.

column13: 1,135,579. Reciprocating generators. NATIONAL RESEARCH DEVELOPMENT CORP. 9 Dec., 1966 [20 Dec., 1965], No. 53782/65. Heading H2A. An electrical generator comprises a member of magnetic material arranged for reciprocating motion, an electrical winding arranged to be energized by direct current to produce magnetic flux, the reluctance of the path for which varies with the position of the member, and means for allowing an alternating output current due to an alternating voltage generated in the winding when the above-mentioned reluctance changes, to be taken, without a substantial direct current component, from the generator. As shown, a cylindrical member 1 reciprocates between the positions shown inside a hollow cylindrical casing 2 around which two coils 3, 4 are provided. When coils 3 and 4 are energized by direct current, the path for flux produced by coil 3 includes the member 1 when it is in the extreme position shown, and the path for flux produced by coil 4 includes the member 1 when it is in the opposite extreme position. Thus the magnitudes of the fluxes alternately vary between maximum and minimum values as member 1 reciprocates. This flux variation induces A.C. in windings 3 and 4, and currents without substantial D.C. components can be extracted from the windings by means such as a transformer coupling. The member 1 may be driven by a single cylinder I.C. engine, or the arrangement 1, 2 may itself constitute the I.C. engine. The invention may take the form of a single cylinder, double piston, arrangement (Fig. 2, not shown). While the direct current may be provided from an external source, part of the A.C. output may be rectified and fed back for D.C. excitation. In the latter case, initial induction may be provided by a small bar magnet extending axially of the piston.

column12: TRANSDUCER OUTPUTTING DIGITAL SIGNAL PROPORTIONAL TO DETECTED VARIATION OF PARAMETER
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide an accurate transducer generating a digital output directly in response to a physical parameter. SOLUTION: Two sinusoidal exciting voltages having a phase shift are applied to a separate pair of resistors 24, 25 or 26, 28 and the voltages at the joint of resistors in respective pairs are subjected to vector addition by means of an adder 33. It is then converted into a rectangular PWM signal and a counter 36 counts the time difference between occurrence of a prominent event of the signal subjected to vector addition (e.g. the moment of time when the voltage value becomes zero, i.e., zerocross point) and occurrence of a similar prominent event of the exciting voltage. The counter 36 produces a digital outputs signal proportional to the variation of a detected physical parameter.

column13: 28. Jackson, A. J. Jan. 1. Loom shuttles, changing bobbins and the like in, automatically ; weft, cutting.-In automatic copchanging looms of the type described in Specification No. 15,867, A.D. 1905, means are provided for retaining and disposing of the free lengths of weft from the cups in the magazine. When a cop a is placed in the magazine b, it is retained at the entrance by a spring or like catch c, and the free end of weft is doubled and laid between fingers e on a brush d or other material having a pile surface. The brush is adjustably carried upon a spindle d', and the requisite length of weft is drawn from the cop and measured by passing it between the fingers when these are laid upon a plate g. The doubled end of weft is held against the bristles of the brush by a spring-pressed plate f, and is laid across guide-rails b<1>, the free end being wound round a pin, or inserted between a band h on rollers h<1> and a band on a pulley i, which may be turned slightly to grip the weft by means of a central knob. The cop is then released from the catch c, and falls down the magazine. In a modified arrangement, the brush is inclined to the vertical and is secured to the back of the magazine. The bristles press against an arm secured to the magazine, and the weft is passed round this arm in contact with the bristles, over the guide-rail b<1>, and secured as described above. When a cop has been inserted in the shuttle, the loose length of weft is drawn out of the brush d, down the guide-rail b<1>, and by means of a guidebar b<2> is directed behind an inclined hook on the shuttle box as the shuttle is picked across the race. Means are described for putting tension on the weft to facilitate the threading of the shuttle, the said means comprising a hook, which is moved downwards by a system of pivoted levers when the lay beats up and engages and draws down the weft to put tension upon it. After the shed hasbeen changed, the end of weft is severed close to the selvedge by a reciprocating or pivoted knife actuated from any suitable part of the loom. The knife-edge may be formed on a bent lever, which is pivoted on the casing of the temple rollers and is provided with a tail-piece. As the lay beats up, an incline thereon acts upon the tail-piece and rocks the bent lever against the action of a spring, so that the knife severs the weft.

A rod 11 of lead having a cylindrical portion 15, a frusto-conical portion 16 and a cylindrical portion 17 and formed integrally with an upstanding lug 12 of a strap of a lead acid battery is passed through a hole in an inter-cell partition 10 and through a hole 21 in a lug 20 of another plate strap. The faces to be connected are degreased in carbon tetrachloride and cleaned with a rotary wire brush and then pressure of 8000-12,000 s.i. is applied to the end of the rod to deform it to fill, and become cold welded to, the hole in the strap lug. Instead of a hole a slot may be formed in the partition, the unoccupied part of which may be filled. Both members may be provided with openings and a separate rod with a tapered portion and cylindrical portion at each end may be cold welded to both members by pressure on its ends.

In apparatus of the type described in Specification 875,330 cigarettes or lengths of mouthpiece material delivered to flutes 8 in a fluted drum and which are to abut against stops 11 are slowed down by a rotating wheel 13 having a frusto-conical hub 13a and a row of cigarette contacting bristles 19. The cigarettes are delivered to the fluted drum by a suction wheel 2 having two helical grooves 4, 5 which deliver cigarettes to the flutes 7 and 8 of the drum respectively. Stops 10 are provided in the flutes 7, the radial distance of the bottoms of the grooves 7 from the centre of the drum being greater than that of the bottoms of the grooves 8. The ends of the grooves are chamfered to the same radial distance from the centre of the drum so that a greater arresting force is applied to cigarettes entering the grooves 7. The wheel 13 is driven in timed relation to the wheel 2 by a belt 18 and the bristles of the brush 19 are arranged so that in operation they run along and with the grooves 8 and exert a progressive force on a cigarette in one of the grooves. Adjustable spring means 20, 24 are provided for exerting a further decelerative force on the cigarettes in the grooves 8 and 7 respectively. The cigarettes are delivered from the drum in two rows to a catcher band 12.

column12: METHOD OF AND CIRCUIT FOR SYNCHRONIZING DATA
column13: Asynchronous DS-1 data is byte synchronized and converted to the SONET VT1.5 format by storing the DS-1 data in a store (20) from which it is read in dependence upon a gapped clock signal (40) which is produced by gapping a first gapped clock signal (48) with a ratio of 208/193, which is the ratio of VT SPE bits per frame to DS-1 bits per frame. The first gapped clock signal is produced by gapping a VT1.5 synchronous clock signal (46). A frequency difference between the first gapped clock signal and the asynchronous data rate, multiplied in a frequency multiplier (26) by the ratio of 208/193, is monitored by comparing the counts of modulo-208 counters (84, 86), and, independence upon the monitored frequency difference, the gapping of the synchronous clock signal is controlled to achieve positive or negative stuffing and hence to compensate for the frequency difference.

column12: An Improved Stop Motion for Automatic Looms.
column13: 29. Jackson, A. J. Jan. 1. Loom slop-motions. -In an automatic bobbin - changing loom of the type described in Specification No. 15,867, A.D. 1905, mechanism is provided for stopping the loom if a bobbin is not properly inserted into the shuttle, or if the bobbin magazine is exhausted or the lowest bobbin therein is sticking. A lever h is pivotei to a bracket at the back of the lay a, and has fingers projecting into the shuttle box above and below the shuttle. If the newly-inserted bobbin projects above or below the shuttle, it strikes one of the fingers on the lever h and rotates the latter, whereby, through an arm a<2> and a sliding rod b on the lay, a pivoted bell-crank lever moves the shipper lever from its notch and stops the loom. The rod b is also moved to stop the loom when the transferrer fails to take a fresh bobbin from the magazine. When a bobbin is taken from the magazine, it . depresses a finger pivoted thereto, and, through suitable mechanism, raises a pivoted cam-piece n out of the path of a projection m<1> on a bell-crank lever m, which is pivoted to the actuating-slide k of the transferrer. When the transferrer fails to take a bobbin from the magazine, the projection m' rides up the cam-piece n, and the upper end of a vertical arm of the lever m strikes a finger o, which is pivoted on the lay. When the finger o is moved, it acts through a pivoted lever p to slide the rod b and thereby stop the loom. When the finger pivoted on the magazine is depressed by a bobbin, it is held down by a pin thereon engaging the underside of the transferrer, in order to keep the cam-piece n inoperative until after the slide k has returned to its normal position.

24,868. Postans, A. J. Nov. 12. Calculating - apparatus. -In an adding-machine, the ratchet k of the units drum 1 of the registering- drums 1, 2, 3 is actuated by a pawl j carried by an arm i on a pinion h, which is rotated by a toothed quadrant g, operated by the engagement of the hooked ends of the levers s of the finger keys t with bars p mounted on T - ended levers n, n<1>, of which the lever n is an arm of the quadrant lever g. To render the stroke of all the finger keys t equal, the bars p are stepped, and the lower row of levers s, which have to give the longer travel to the quadrant g, engage the bars p at a greater distance from the axis than the upper levers. Thus the depression of a finger key t causes the quadrant g to travel through an arc, the length of which is dependent on the number on the finger key depressed, and the pawl j to travel over a corresponding number of teeth on the ratchetwheel k. On releasing the finger key, the spring v returns the quadrant g to its normal position, thereby moving the pinion h, the lever i, and the pawl j in the reverse direction, turning the ratchet k and the drum l the number of teeth or spaces represented by the number on the key depressed. The hooks on the levers, s prevent the overrunning of the quadrant g, and the overrunning of the drum is prevented by a stop l abutting against a spring detent m, while a spring detent 16 prevents the drum from turning in the backward direction. The carrying over from one drum to the next can be effected in any known manner, or by the mechanism shown in Fig. 5, in which a snail cam 8 on the drum, as it revolves, gradually raises the lever 10 and pawl 15 in opposition to a spring 15<a> until the pin 9, having arrived at the highest point of the cam 8, suddenly drops and causes the ratchet 12 and the drum to move one tooth or division, its further movement being prevented by a stop 10<a>. The return of the indicating-drums to their zero position to enable a fresh addition to be made is effected by a handwheel 5, which is normally locked by a stud 17 and a spring catch 7. After the wheel 5 has been released by pressing the axle d against the spring 6 and by holding back the catch 7, it is turned, causing a lever q to rock the quadrant g and disengage the pawl k, so that the units drum 1 can be moved into the zero line when pins 18 on the drums or snail cams are engaged by pins 19 on the axle d.

column12: Automated volser range management for removable media storage library
column13: When an automated data storage library includes the capability of storing and accessing more than one media type, it is necessary for the library manager to keep track of what media type is associated with each volume serial number ("VOLSER"), and where each is physically located in the library. For efficiency, VOLSERs will be grouped in sequential ranges, each range associated with a single media type (although a particular media type can be associated with different, non-contiguous ranges). When the number of VOLSERs and ranges is small, new ranges can be easily added, and existing ranges can be easily deleted or modified, manually by a system administrator. However, when the number of VOLSERs and ranges becomes large, it becomes burdensome for the administrator to track the VOLSER ranges and media types. An automated VOLSER range management system is provided which detects whether a new or modified range overlaps or is adjacent to an existing range with the same media type. If so, the system automatically combines the ranges.

column13: 739,040. Ordnance; fuze setting devices. ROSE BROS. (GAINSBOROUGH), Ltd. Dec. 7, 1945 Nov. 8, 1944], No. 21977/44. Class 92(2). A fuze-setting device attached to the barrel 11 of a gun comprises two wire gripper units 36 which stretch a wire 81 across the muzzle so that a highvoltage can be applied to the wire for the purpose of manipulating the fuze of a projectile as it leaves the muzzle. The gripper units 36 are rotatably mounted and diametrically arranged on a carrier 21, 21, which is itself rotatable within a casing 16, 17, 14 about a supporting member 11. The carrier 21, 22 is driven intermittently by a continually rotating electric motor 32 through gearing 23, 24, whenever a clutch 29 is engaged. The clutch mechanism is similar to that described in detail in Specification 602,829, [Group XXIV]. When no wire extends between the gripper units to complete an electric circuit, a solenoid 101 is so energized that the clutch 29 engages and the carrier 21, 22 moves through 180 degrees before the clutch is disengaged. Each gripper unit is mounted on a ball race 60 and comprises semi-circular jaws 41, 42 which are caused to grip a wire 81 at the correct times bv the movement of a roller 57 engaging a track 58. The wire is fed from a rotatable reel 82 through a pivoted cover member 86. When the gun is fired the recoil motion actuates a changeover switch to apply a high voltage to the wire 81 and subsequently to restore the low-tension supply to the solenoid. The projectile breaks the wire and the blast forces the free ends against cutters 73. During rotation of the carrier a friction roller 43 engages tracks 76, 77 thereby oscillating the gripper unit approaching the feeder 83 so that it discharges any remaining wire fragment. Insulators 122 prevent flashover.

column13: A X-ray emissive vacuum tube is fully enclosed in an electrically conductive casing with electrical terminals through which bias potentials are applied to the tube. Class 9(i) A shield 1 to position an electric detonator in an explosive charge and to protect it from accidental initiation has an upper body portion 2 and a lower threaded portion 3 of reduced diameter. Formed in the shield is a through passage 4 for a detonator and extending from the passage 4 across the concave top 6 of the shield is a slot 5 continued diagonally across the shield to the lower end of the passage 4. The upper part of the slot is sufficiently wide and deep to accommodate two insulated leading wires, while the lower part of the slot will hold from leading wires without any of the wires projecting beyond the contour of the shield. The opposite end of the canister has an externally threaded projection 10 adapted to engage a recessed threaded portion 11 of a canister 12 containing blasting explosive. Several canisters 12 may be screwed together to form a column of explosive. With larger charges the shield may be screwed into an adapter similar to the recessed part 8, a detonator tube being screwed into the adapter. To use the shield an electric detonator is passed upwards through the hole 4 taking part of the lead wires with it. The wires are then pressed into the slot 5 and their free ends brought upwards along the diagonal part of the slot while the detonator is inserted in the tube 9 and the shield is screwed into the recess 8. The shield is preferably of non-metallic and non-electrically conducting material, e.g. wood, hard rubber or synthetic resins.

A pivot position sensor sensing outboard motor trim includes a housing within which a pair of U-shaped movable contacts are secured in axially spaced relation on an operating rod which extends outwardly of the housing. The housing is attached by the motor. The end of the rod is interconnected by a flexible cable to a clamp coupler affixed to the tilt tube or shaft. The cable extends over the collar and wraps and unwraps thereon as the motor pivots to position the rod with respect to the motor. The fixed housing is provided with a chamber having a pair of wound linear resistor units secured in longitudinal recesses on opposite sides of the chamber and engaged by one of said contacts. At ninety degrees therefrom, a pair of limit contact strips are mounted in offset recesses on opposite sides of the chamber and connected by the other contact. At a preselected up-tilted position, the limit contacts separate from the strips and open the circuit therebetween to terminate up-trim drive.

column13: 894,310. Dish-washing machines. COLSTON Ltd., CHARLES. Dec. 2, 1950 [Jan. 13, 1960; Feb. 18, 1960], Nos. 1311/60 and 5854/60. Class 138 (1). In a dish-washing machine having a washing chamber through or within which washing liquid is caused to circulate continuously the washing liquid is filtered by a main filter through which all or the greater part of the circulating liquid passes and a secondary filter or filters of finer mesh through which only a part of the circulating liquid is permitted or constrained to pass. As illustrated in Fig. 1 the dish-washing machine has a rotary impeller as described in Specification 832,756 for discharging spray on to the dishes to be washed, which are arranged in racks R 1 , R 2 in a cabinet C. The main filter (not shown) consists of a disc of open mesh gauze detachably fitted in the sump S, and the secondary filter F is suspended between a side runner for the rack R 2 and the cabinet wall. The filter F consists of a bag or pouch of fine mesh, e.g. of nylon, attached to a wire frame the upper parallel members 3, 4 of which are more widely spaced than the lower members 5 to provide an open mouth to collect the soiled water running down the cabinet wall. The lower part of the bag is held away from the cabinet wall by a member 7 so that the filtered liquid passes through both walls of the bag. To prevent overspilling caused by foam present in the washing liquid the filter bag may have a narrow throat near its mouth. Alternatively a bimetallic element may be disposed in the mouth of the filter bag which flexes as the temperature of the washing liquid rises during the washing operation to reduce the size of the mouth opening. Overspilling of foam may also be prevented by alternately inclined baffles arranged in the filter bag. In two further constructions the secondary filter is arranged opposite one end of the impeller tube T, and above the main filter in the sump S, respectively.

column13: The present invention discloses a generator ( 1 ) able to generate either unidirectional current or bi-directional current. A rotatable disc ( 7 ) has a conductive track ( 9 ) and a ferromagnetic bridge ( 8 ). Brushes ( 12, 13 ) switchingly open circuit a coil ( 16 ) or connect the coil ( 16 ) to a load resistor (R). Movement of the disc ( 7 ) results in bridge ( 8 ) shunting a core ( 15 ) of the coil ( 16 ). This generates an emf in the coil ( 16 ). If the circuit is closed, current flows in the resistor (R). If the circuit is open, no current flows. The arrangement is such that current only flows when the bridge ( 8 ) approaches the magnet ( 14 )-not when the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ). Thus, only the magnetic attraction for the bridge ( 8 ) by the magnet ( 14 ) impedes the movement of the disc ( 7 ) as the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ) without the disc's movement also being impeded by generation of electric current at that time.

Handles, door etc.; handles, attaching; escutcheons, keyhole. - Relates to handles, especially such as are used for furniture and the like, which are made in three distinct parts, namely, a handle proper, a bracket or brackets, and a back-plate. The brackets are provided with bases at rightangles to the part in which the handle is swung and are secured to the back-plate by screws or other means. In some cases, the brackets are T-shaped, thus providing bases on both sides of the projecting parts, the bases being imperforate and secured by the clamping action of the backplate ; or the base of the bracket may be discshaped, the projecting part being, if desired, stamped or pressed out of the substance of the disc. When a single bracket is employed, the back-plate may be provided at its upper part with a keyhole slot, so as to form an escutcheon to a keyhole, and, if desired, the base of the bracket may be carried upwards and slotted to form a backing for the keyhole of the base-plate. The back-plate is cut with a single horizontal slot, and the bracket is formed of a strip of metal, bent round the handle to form an eye, and is secured by screws or other means. In the form shown in Fig. 26, the base c<1> of the bracket d is fixed on the front of the back-plate b by a screw e, and part of the base c<1> is stamped to form two spikes or tongues c', which are driven into the article of furniture a. The back-plate may be formed with a vertical slot, through which projects a perforated bracket the base of which is secured to the backplate by a screw, the handle being split and a pin passed through the two ends thereof and through the perforation in the bracket. In the form shown in Fig. 32, the strip of metal forming the bracket c is bent to form a socket, into which is fitted the end of a transversely-perforated latch spindle or the like f. A pin d<2> is passed through the ends of the handle d, the socket in the bracket c, and the perforation in the spindle f. The back-plate b is fixed to the article independently of the bracket c, which may thus turn with the handle and the latch spindle.

column12: Improvements in or relating to Starting Mechanism for Explosion Engines.
column13: 22,460. Postans, A. J. Oct. 22. Gas engines, igniting in. For starting an engine the magneto is driven by gearing so arranged that the armature can be revolved and the distributing commutator momentarily angularly displaced in relation to the engine. Mounted on the armature shaft is one member B', Fig. 1, of a differential gear, the case of which B<5> carrying the intermediate members B<4> has fixed to it a sprocket-wheel B<6> driven from the halfspeed shaft by a chain B<8>. The remaining member B<2> carries a drum B<3>, around which the chains C, C' are half-lapped. The chain Cis connected through a plunger D', Fig. 2, a spring cylinder D, and an end chain D<4>, to the usual spark-adjusting lever, the compressed spring D' being stiff enough to act as a rigid connexion and the drum being returned to its original position on release of the lever by a tension spring C<3>. The chain C<1> is connected to a pedal to enable the drum B<3> to be rotated at starting, compressing the spring, D' (since the chain D<4> is fixed), and retarding the distributing-commntator ; the latter is of the type described in Specification No. 17.463, A.D. 1907, or of other suitable form, and is geared to the other end of the armature shaft. The first charge is thus fired, and, on release of the starting-pedal, the spring D' returns the drum B<3> to the position determined by the spark-adjusting lever. The positions of the sprocket B<6> and the drum B<3> may be interchanged, and, if the armature speed is any multiple of that of the engine, the commutator is geared down to agree with the latter.

column12: An improved expansible mandrel for sinking tubes into the ground
column13: 728,211. Piles. FRANKI FOUNDATION CO. Dec. 30, 1953, No. 36162/53. Class 68(2) In an expansible mandrel for driving sheet metal tubes into the ground, having a central member 12 and sectors 3 in which pneumatically controlled expansion chambers provide a radial thrust to support the tubes during driving, a separate set of pneumatic chambers is provided for the contraction of the mandrel. Preferably, each chamber is a longitudinally extending rubber pipe, each pipe 19 of one set being in radial alignment with a pipe 18 of the other set. The pipes are closed at their lower ends, and the admission of fluid under pressure to pipes 19 forces the arms 17 and 11 apart, contracts the mandrel, and flattens pipes 18 against their resilient tendency to assume a circular form. On inflating pipes 18, pipes 19 offer no resistance to flattening and the sectors 3 are guided radially outwards by arms 9. Upper casing 6 is attached by bolts 7 which allow for the radial movement of the sectors 3, and is provided with a wooden block 24 to receive hammer blows. These are transmitted to the central member 12 through resilient washer 15. Lugs 25 are provided for the with-, drawal of the mandrel, after which the tube 1 which may be conical or have a smooth wall, is filled with concrete or like. The lower end of the tube may be covered by a plate 2 of metal or concrete or may be sealed with a plug of concrete.

column13: A method for providing a cellular phone user with accurate feedback of available minutes in a service plan based on specific plan usage is disclosed. column13: Disclosed are systems, methods, and devices for presenting personalized map labels. In one embodiment, the method comprises receiving a request for a map; retrieving a user profile associated with the identification of the user; identifying merchant information within a predefined distance from the location of the user; identifying a correlation between the user profile and the merchant information; ranking the merchant information based on the correlation identified between the user profile and the merchant information; generating one or more labels based on the ranking of the merchant information; and transmitting map data and the one or more labels to the user.

column13: 1277333 Semi-conductor devices GENERAL MOTORS CORP 16 July 1970 [31 July 1969] 34517/70 Heading H1K A silicon planar PNP transistor comprises a P-type wafer 12 having one surface 14 with a refractory oxide coating overlain by aluminium contacts 20, 22. Within the wafer are surface extending conductivity regions; an N-type base 24; a P-type emitter 26 and a P+ expanded guard ring 28; the collector being the remainder of the wafer to define a collector base PN junction 32 and an emitter base PN junction 34. The base 24 is surrounded by a narrow collector border 36, and guard ring 28 surrounds base 24 non-contiguously and border 36 contiguously; extending to the periphery of surface 14 with inserted semi-circular collector islands 38, 40 spacedly adjacent from opposite sides of border 36. A thick layer 42 of silicon oxide overlays islands 38, 40 and border 36 while a thin layer 44 of oxide overlays guard ring 28 and a portion of emitter 26, and an intermediate thickness oxide coating overlap the base-emitter junction. Contacts 20, 22 are electrically connected to emitter 26 and base 24 and comprise bonding pads 48, 50 overlying islands 38, 40 with inwardly-extending interdigitated electrodes 49, 51 engaging base and emitter through openings of the oxide, and wire connectors 52, 54 are pressure bonded to pads 48, 50. In manufacture, surface 12 is cleaned and oxidized, a window etched therein for N-type diffusion to form base 24; reoxidized and etched to form a further smaller window overlying the base for P-type diffusion for the emitter 26. Oxide is also removed from the surface from border 32 to the perimeter except for the overlying islands 38, 40 to allow diffusion to form P + guard ring 28, followed by further oxidation. Openings in the oxide overlying emitter 26 and base 24 are etched for contacts, and aluminium contacts 20, 22 evaporated on with interdigitated electrodes connecting to base and emitter.

Over the bared ends of an electric cable 30, Fig. 4, is placed a metal sleeve 32 which has a serrated internal surface and an axial bar 36 threaded into one end, the bar having a tapered extremity that penetrates and expands the cable end to force it into tight contact with the serrations. The outer portion of the bar 36 is enlarged at 40 to engage a recess 42 in the shackle 10 so that the cable may be drawn through the oversize tube 2 after which the end of the latter is crimped in order that the whole may be drawn through a reducing die, not shown, to force the tube into contact with the cable body, the reduced crimped end facilitating entry into the die. column12: Up-converted and amplified transmission signal using log-antilog
column13: According to one exemplary embodiment, a method for producing an up-converted and amplified transmission signal comprises performing a logarithmic transformation of an input transmission signal to form a logarithmically transformed transmission signal, adding the logarithmically transformed transmission signal to a logarithmic local oscillator signal to form a sum signal, and performing an antilogarithmic transformation of the sum signal to produce the up-converted and amplified transmission signal. In one embodiment, a log-antilog circuit for producing an up-converted and an amplified transmission signal comprises a transmission log block configured to receive an input transmission signal and to provide a logarithmically transformed transmission signal as a transmission log block output, and an antilog block coupled to the transmission log block. The antilog block is configured to receive a sum signal of the transmission log block output and a logarithmic local oscillator signal.

column12: Particle filled rubbers prodn - by bonding solid particles to grooved rubber pellets
column13: Process comprises (a) converting the rubber material into granules or pellets with a grooved or notched surface; (b) adding to these granules or pellets an agent for improving the retention power of their surfaces relative to the solid particles, and (c) distributing the solid particles over the surfaces of the granules or pellets, so that the particles adhere to the surfaces. Uniform distribution of the particles is obtained. The powder is easily retained during storage and transport, as the major part is present in the grooves or notches and thus is protected against pressure or friction.

column12: Prevention of atherosclerosis using NADPH oxidase inhibitors
column13: A method for the prevention and treatment of atherosclerosis and its related diseases in mammals is provided, in which an NADPH oxidase inhibitor is administered to mammals. The NADPH oxidase inhibitor prevents the production of reactive oxygen species upon exposure of endothelial cells to atherogenic LDL levels, resulting in decreased endocytosis and vascular hyperpermeability. Apocynin is a preferred NADPH oxidase inhibitor. Additionally, there is provided a diagnostic method for predicting the risk to an individual of atherosclerotic-related diseases.

column12: Log-antilog circuit and method for producing an up-converted and amplified transmission signal
column13: According to one exemplary embodiment, a method for producing an up-converted and amplified transmission signal comprises performing a logarithmic transformation of an input transmission signal to form a logarithmically transformed transmission signal, adding the logarithmically transformed transmission signal to a logarithmic local oscillator signal to form a sum signal, and performing an antilogarithmic transformation of the sum signal to produce the up-converted and amplified transmission signal. In one embodiment, a log-antilog circuit for producing an up-converted and an amplified transmission signal comprises a transmission log block configured to receive an input transmission signal and to provide a logarithmically transformed transmission signal as a transmission log block output, and an antilog block coupled to the transmission log block. The antilog block is configured to receive a sum signal of the transmission log block output and a logarithmic local oscillator signal.

column13: Le procédé de purification d'un sel précurseur chloro, bromo ou iodo de zirconium, hafnium ou aluminium consiste à utiliser un corps thermique en fusion (10) d'un ou de plusieurs halogénures de métal alcalin ou alcalino-terreux et le sel précurseur contenant des impuretés, à maintenir le corps à une température suffisante pour volatiliser le sel précurseur (16) en l'éloignant de ses impuretés tout en effectuant une réduction dans le corps au moyen d'un agent réducteur fluide, mobile (11) qui est non réducteur pour le sel précurseur, et à isoler le sel précurseur volatilisé purifié du corps. Le sel précurseur volatilisé isolé ultra-purifié peut ensuite réagir (20) avec un agent de fluoration pour produire le fluorure très purifié utilisé dans du verre de qualité fibre optique ou autre.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR IMPROVING NEIGHBOR SEARCHING PERFORMANCE
column13: In a system for mobile wireless communication, it is desirable to minimize the period of time during which the RF circuitry is powered (i.e. the RF power period). A novel method and apparatus for pilot monitoring during standby mode defers processing of pilot search results until the RF power period has passed. This approach allows more searches to be performed without extending the RF power period, thus improving idle handoff performance without reducing battery charge life.

column13: Disclosed are systems, methods, and devices for providing real-time inventory information. In one embodiment, the method comprises receiving a catalog of products offered for sale by one or more merchants; generating in-store catalogs for each of the one or more merchants, an in-store catalog representing products sold by a store operated by a merchant and an inventory count for each product sold by the store; receiving a product request from a user; identifying one or more related products based on the product request, each of the one or more related products being associated with a store; determining inventory counts associated with each of the one or more related products based on the in-store catalogs associated with the one or more related products; generating a list of in-stock products based on the inventory counts; and transmitting the list of in-stock products to the user in response to the product request.

column12: Improvements relating to measuring methods and apparatus
column13: 952,074. Magnetic tests. DAVY & UNITED ENGINEERING CO. Ltd. July 26,1961 [July 26, 1960], No. 25946/60. Heading G1N. The elongation of magnetisable material as it passes through rolling means is determined by magnetising parts of the material at first points on the entry and exit sides of the rolling means, and generating electrical signals as the magnetised parts pass further points on the entry and exit sides, the magnetising taking place simultaneously with the generation of a signal at one of the further points, whereby the time separation of the signals is a measure of the elongation, and of the difference in speeds of the material at either side of the rolling means. Steel strip 5 passes between rollers 6 and passes close to transmitters 12, 12<SP>1</SP>, which magnetise the strip, and receivers 7, 7<SP>1</SP> which generate signals as magnetised parts of the strip pass them. Signals from receiver 7 pass through amplifier 8, pulse shaper 9, triggered pulse generator 10 and power amplifier driving circuit 11 to transmitter 12, so that pulses are generated continuously at a frequency depending on the speed of the strip and the separation of the transmitter and receiver. These pulses are fed through a D. C. restoring circuit 13 and a low-pass filter 14 to an indicator 15 measuring the ingoing strip speed. The system is triggered by a freerunning pulse generator 16 (e.g. at 1 pulse/sec.), below the minimum frequency (e.g. 3 pulses/sec.) of the speed measuring apparatus, generator 16 being biased off by bias amplifier 17 once the apparatus has been started. Generator 10 also operates transmitter 12<SP>1</SP>, and the separation of each transmitter from its corresponding receiver is made the same. The pulses generated by receiver 7<SP>1</SP> are fed through amplifier 8<SP>1</SP> and shaper 9<SP>1</SP> to pulse generator 10<SP>1</SP>, and the outputs from generators 10, 10<SP>1</SP> are fed to a pulse generator 18, which produces pulses whose width is proportional to the time separation of the input pulses. These pulses are applied through a D. C. restoring circuit 19 and filter 20 to an indicator 21 giving a signal proportional to the product of pulse width and pulse frequency, which is substantially proportional to the elongation of the strip, for small elongations. In a modification, suitable for measuring large elongations,transmitter 12 and receiver 7 are placed at the output side of rollers 6 and units 7<SP>1</SP>, 12<SP>1</SP> at the input side so that the frequency of the pulses applied to both transmitters is proportional to the outgoing strip speed, instead of the ingoing speed. A switch 22 is provided for zero-point calibration and checking purposes.

column12: Improvements in or relating to a method of fastening together pieces of material
column13: 1,106,439. Welding by pressure. GENERAL ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. 13 Oct., 1966 [26 Oct., 1965], No. 45351/65. Heading B3R. In fastening together pieces of material the pieces are lapped with apertures in each piece aligned to form a hole through the pieces, a fastener of cold'weldable material is arranged at each end of the hole and the central parts of the fasteners are cold welded through the hole to each other or to opposite sides of a junction piece of cold weldable material within the hole. Each of two sheets 11, 12, Fig. 1, has a portion bent at right angles to form flanges 14 15 in which oval holes 16 are punched, the holes are aligned and V shaped aluminium fasteners 17 are slid over the flanges to cover the holes. A hand operated hand tool having opposed multiple dies applies pressure to the limbs 18, 19 of the fasteners to effect welds 21, Fig. 2. The sheets 11, 12 may each be a layer of paper sandwiched between two layers of aluminium foil when the fasteners may cold weld to the foil. Instead of V-shaped fasteners separate plates may be employed one of which may extend beyond the flanges being joined to form e.g. an electrical terminal. Instead of opposed dies a single die and a backing platen may be used when one fastener only is pressed into the hole. In a further example for joining paper layers 11, 12 having metal layers 33, Fig. 7, on one side only a junction strip 32 of aluminium is inserted between the flanges to contact the metal layers and U-shaped fastener 17 is provided to cover holes 16, the fastener being cold welded through the holes to the junction strip. The junction piece may be extended to form a contact terminal 35. Copper may be used for the fasteners and junction piece and the junction piece may be centrally cranked. Holes which may be circular may be drilled.

Known fishing rod holders suffer from a large number of problems. As they are non adjustable, they hold the rods fixed in one position. The rods generally need to be removed for adjustment or re rigging as well as to boat a catch. When trolling rods are set in one position which can result in entanglement. Also, when travelling, the rods protrude laterally outside the craft which can result in damage to rods and/or the craft. Herein disclosed is a rotatable flush mounted fishing rod holder including a rod holding tube with an annular flange extending radially from an upper end thereof, and an annular cover member to attach relative to a surface over the annular flange to hold the rod holding tube to the surface but allow rotation of the rod holding tube relative thereto. The holder further includes an annular cover member adapted to attach to the surface and the annular member over the annular flange to hold the rod holding tube to the surface but allow rotation of the rod holding tube relative to the surface and the annular cover member, wherein the rod holding tube has an open end for receiving a rod, wherein the annular flange is located between the annular cover member and the annular member, wherein the rod holding tube defines a longitudinal axis that is rotatable around a perpendicular axis of the annular cover member.

The retaining mechanism comprises a body 56 with a bore 58 therein containing a release member 54 that supports a projecting retainer formation 52 engaging and retaining the stretched band about the rod. The release member 54 is arranged to be moved longitudinally along the bore until it reaches a position where the stretched band acts to rotate it within the bore toward a disengaged orientation where the stretched band is no longer engaged by the retainer formation, e.g. by sliding the retainer formation along an L-shaped guide slot 68. A user rapidly uncouples the rod by shunting the release member along the bore until the retainer formation pivots to release the elastic loop. Paddle-wheels.-Relates to means for propelling ships of the type in which one or more sliding blades d<2>, Figs. 4 and 5, are adapted to be extended and withdrawn through peripheral slots in an immersed cylindrical casing a<2> under the action of a stationary cam or eccentrically-mounted disk g. A pair of drums a<2> are arranged end to end at the stern of the ship, and are mounted upon a non- rotating shaft c rigidly supported by brackets. Each paddle-wheel is provided with a single reciprocating blade the ends of which project alternately through slots in the opposite sides of the drum, the mechanism being arranged so that the blades of the respective drums slide simultaneously but in opposite directions. The drums are driven directly by bevel-gearing from the main engine shaft. The blades slide between guides f secured to the inner sides of the drum ends, the middle parts of the blades being of a flat tubular form. Where narrower blades are used, each drum may be provided with two or more blades in which case the drums are provided with circumferential flanges to minimize lateral slip of the water, the drums being driven from separate engine shafts. A pair of drums may be rotated in opposite directions, the arrangement being such that the operative parts of the blades act on opposite sides of the centre line of the shaft.

The connections needed to provide access from a user station to the central station, or vice versa, are set up in normal "digital exchange manner" via the telecommunication system, which is usually a digital PABX. With several microprocessors at the central station access is via a hunting group number, or one of two or more such numbers for different computing applications.

column12: OPTICAL OFDM TRANSMISSION WITH IMPROVED EFFICIENCY
column13: A method of transmitting digital information over a dispersive optical channel (106) comprises encoding (152) the digital information into a series of data blocks, wherein each block comprises a plurality of substantially orthogonal frequency domain subcarriers, each data block is then divided (154) into at least two frequency bands, each band comprising a plurality of contiguous subcarriers. A frequency/time transformation is then performed (156), in order to form a corresponding plurality of transformed bands, each transformed band comprising a sequence of time domain data samples. A time delay is applied (158) to at least one of the transformed bands relative to at least one other of the transformed bands. The bands are then combined (160) to produce an electrical signal waveform embodying the digital information. Finally, an optical source is modulated (162) using the electrical signal waveform, to produce a corresponding optical signal for transmission over the dispersive optical channel (106). The invention enables a reduction in the duration of guard intervals that may need to be inserted into the transmitted data blocks, in order to avoid received signal degradation due to inter-symbol interference caused by dispersion in the optical channel (106). Transmission overheads may thereby be reduced, resulting in an improvement in transmission efficiency.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR IMPROVING RECEPTION OF OPTICAL SIGNALS
column13: A method and apparatus for receiving digital information transmitted via an optical signal over an optical channel wherein the optical signal includes an optical carrier ( 402 ) and at least one information-bearing optical sideband ( 404 ) in the optical frequency domain. The transmitted optical power is distributed between the optical carrier ( 402 ) and the optical side band ( 404 ). The received optical signal is processed in order to increase the received power in the optical carrier ( 402 ) relative to the power in the optical side-band ( 404 ). The processed optical signal is detected in order to produce a corresponding electrical signal. The electrical signal is then processed in order to recover the digital information. Advantageously, increasing the optical carrier power relative to the power in the information-bearing sideband results in improved quality of the detected electrical signal, enabling an improved power budget to be achieved, which in turn allows for longer transmission distances, increased transmitted information rates, and/or improved transmission error performance as compared with conventional direct detection optical transmission systems.

1,106,811. Automatic control. McDONNELL AIRCRAFT CORPORATION. March 22, 1965, No.12103/65. Heading G3R. In a network for removing an undesired component, e. g. from an error signal in an aircraft automatic guidance system, an input signal is sampled at intervals and the digital signals so produced stored and repeatedly up-dated for comparison with signals of similar form derived from a digital computer to correspond to an estimate of the desired component of the input signal. Differences between the two sets of signals should have characteristics corresponding to the undesired component and any inaccuracy in this respect is applied to repeatedly up-date the computer produced signals so that they are continuously improved and can be utilized as the output of the network for control purposes. In the arrangement described, computer selection from a family of damped oscillatory signals improves until the comparison signals are undamped and thus correspond to undesired airframe vibration components. Besides discrimination in dependence on damping discrimination may also depend on amplitude phase or frequency and the computer may deal with these characteristics in succession.

[Also in Division G4] Apparatus for controlling a moving member, e.g. for stopping a ram on a forging press, measures the position of two points on the member and calculates the mean of the two points. In the forging press control circuit shown bidirection counters 22A, 22B operated by pulses from transducers 16, 17 indicate vertical movements of the ends of the crosshead A, B. When the counter 22A reaches a value, determined by a selector 25, corresponding to a fixed position reached by the lower end A of a tilted crosshead a gate 29A is opened and a counter 23A measures further downward movements of the end A. When it reaches a pre-set value, also determined by the selector 25, and indicating that the end A has reached a predetermined level 14, a comparator 24A produces an enabling signal on a line 65, which signal sets a trigger in a circuit 27 and also opens a gate 26B. This taps the outputs of a gate 29B to a counter 23B, which operates similarly to the counter 23A, and after delaying the pulse trains re-combines them with the original signals in a twin OR gate 28B so that the counter 23B counts two pulses for each unit of downward movement of the end B. Thus if the end B is at a height D above the end A when gate 26B is opened a signal is given on a line 56 when the end B has dropped a distance D/2. The signal on line 56 causes a second trigger in the circuit 27 to open an AND gate and stop the press in known manner. At this point the mid-point C of the crosshead is on the level 14.

Gel-retarded miscible and pumpable crutcher slurry
column13: A miscible and pumpable crutcher slurry comprises 40-70% solids and 60-30% water. The solids consist of 20-45% (wt.)NaHCO3; 10-30% Na2CO3; 5-25% Na silicate of Na20/SiO2 ratio 1:1.4-3; and 10-65% zeolite. The slurry also contains either (A) 0.1-2% citric acid or a water-soluble citrate and 0.1-1.4% Mg sulphate (total at least 0.4%); or (B) 0.3-3% Mg citrate or acid citrate. The ratio of NaHCO3 to Na2CO3 is 1-4:1, the ratio of Na2CO3 to Na silicate is 1:2.5-5:1, the ratio of NaHCO3 to Na silicate is 1-8:1 and the ratio of zeolite to silicate is 1:2-10:1. Gelation and setting of the slurry is retarded and often prevented by (A) or (B). The improved workability of the mixt. permits mfr. of higher solids content slurries, giving significant energy savings and improvements in prodn. rates when the slurries are spray dried to bead form for use in detergent compsns.

column12: Method and apparatus for improving neighbor searching performance
Method and apparatus for adapting antenna array to reduce adaptation time while increasing array performance
column13: An antenna apparatus that can increase capacity in a cellular communication system is disclosed. The antenna operates in conjunction with a mobile subscriber unit and comprises a plurality of antenna elements, each coupled to a respective weight control component to provide a weight to the signal transmitted from (or received by) each element. The weight for each antenna element is adjusted to achieve optimum reception during, for example, an idle mode when a pilot signal is received. The antenna array creates a beam former for signals to be transmitted from the mobile subscriber unit, and a directional receiving array to more optimally detect and receive signals transmitted from the base station. By directionally receiving and transmitting signals, multipath fading and intercell interference are greatly reduced. The weights are adjusted in a coarse and a fine mode. In the coarse mode all the weight control components are jointly adjusted or changed so that the antenna beam scans through a predetermined sector of a circle until a signal quality metric of the received signal is optimized. The coarse adjustment mode is followed by a fine adjustment mode during which the weights of are independently adjusted to further optimize the signal quality metric.

column13: 1,041,449. Endless conveyers. LAMSON ENGINEERING CO. Ltd. May 27, 1965 [May 28, 1964 (2)], Nos. 22105/64 and 22106/64. Heading B8A. An elevator having ascending and descending runs A, D between several floors of a building comprises an endless chain 10 carrying at spaced intervals load carriers C which pass adjacent article dispatch and receiving stations during the ascending and descending runs respectively, a mechanism associated with each of the said stations to sense the condition of the station and the adjacent carrier before initiating the dispatch or receiving operation. Each carrier comprises two horizontal article carrying arms 30, 31 secured to an arm 22 attached to the chain 10 and a back plate 20 attached to the arm 22 mounts rollers 23, 24 at top and bottom to run on guides 25, 26, 27, whereby the carrier is maintained at the same attitude throughout the full circuit. At a dispatch station, an article carriage 45, Fig. 2 (not shown), is horizontally rollable into the path of the carrier C which passes up through the carriage lifting an article thereon, therefrom. Before the dispatch carriage can move into the path of the carrier C, a series of dispatch mechanism switches must be operated. The latter comprise (in Fig. 4, not shown) a switch 101 on the carriage operated by an article thereon, a normally closed switch 105 which must remain closed indicating that there is no article already on the carriage and a switch 111 momentarily operated by the carrier as it approaches the station, to activate a holding circuit for a solenoid 120. The said switch operation indicates that an article is on the carriage ready for dispatch and the approaching article carrier C is empty, whereupon a holding circuit is established for the dispatch carriage moving mechanism. The latter mechanism comprises a link and gear arrangement, Figs. 3 and 4 (not shown), which is actuated by an extension of the ascending carrier engaging a free end of the linkage, the free end being moved into the path of said extension by a solenoid energized through the said holding circuit. The mechanism moves the carriage towards and away from the elevator whereafter the ascending carrier operates a switch for breaking the said holding circuit. The receiving mechanism and its control is similar to that of dispatch except that activation of a particular station mechanism depends on a pair of trip switches being closed by a like pair of trip levers mounted on the carrier, whereby the receiving station may be selected. A combination of trip levers carried on each carrier C is selectively set at the dispatch station by trip setting levers, Fig. 6 (not shown). The latter levers are preselected to move into a tripping position under control of a solenoid energized when the dispatch mechanism circuit is energized and are returned when the associated holding circuit is broken. In a further embodiment, Figs. 14-20 (not shown), the article is dispatched to or received from the elevator by a platform movable between a conveyer and the elevator on a parallel arm supporting structure. A linkage system associated with the structure is movable under solenoid control into the path of a sensing member on the carrier, whereupon engagement occurs and the movement of the platform is mechanically controlled by the moving carrier.

A FORMING APPARATUS FOR FORMING A WEB FROM STOCK
column13: A forming apparatus (10) is disclosed for forming a web (W) from stock (S) ejected from a headbox (12). The apparatus (10) includes a fourdrinier wire (14) which defines a substantially horizontal section (16) having a first and a second end (18, 20). A headbox (12) is disposed adjacent to and above the first end (18) of the horizontal section (16) for ejecting the stock (S) onto the fourdrinier wire (22) between the first and the second end (18, 20) of the section (16). A looped forming wire (22) cooperates with and is disposed above the horizontal section (16) such that the fourdrinier wire (14) and the forming wire (22) define therebetween an elongate forming section (24) for removing water from the stock (S), the forming section (24) having an upstream and a downstream end (26, 28). A curved forming shoe (30) is disposed adjacent to the uspstream end (26) of the forming section (24) and on an opposite side of the fourdrinier wire (14) relative to the headbox (12). The arrangement is such that during movement of the fourdrinier wire (14) over the curved shoe (30), water (32) is thrown centrifugally from the stock (S) to the forming wire (22). A vacuum slot (34) is disposed on an opposite side of the wires (14, 22) relative to the shoe (30) for conveying the water (32) removed centrifugally through the forming wire (22). A curved inverted vacuum box (36) is disposed immediately downstream relative to the vacuum slot (34) and on the same side of the wires (14, 22) as the vacuum slot (34). The curved box (36) defines a curved face (38) for guiding the wires (14, 22). The curved face (38) is curved in an opposite sense relative to the curved forming shoe (30). A looped blanket (40) is disposed on the same side of the wires (14, 22) as the shoe (30), the blanket (40) being disposed adjacent to and on the opposite side of the wires (14, 22) relative to the curved face (38). The blanket (40) cooperates with the fourdrinier wire (14) for pressing the fourdrinier wire (14) against the curved face (38) for urging a further portion of water (42) away from the formed web (W) and through the forming wire (22).

column12: Improvements in or relating to delay blasting devices
column13: 708,422. Blasting devices. IMPERIAL CHEMICAL INDUSTRIES, Ltd. June 15, 1951 [June 15, 1950], No. 14950/50. Class 9(1) Blasting device for connecting detonating fuze to a plurality of explosive charges for detonation at predetermined intervals comprises a tubular metal sheath 1 surrounding a metal detonator tube 2 and connected at one end to a length 3 of flexible detonating fuze and crimped at the other end to a thick-walled tube 6 of soft rubber or neoprene. At the opposite end of the tube 6 is crimped a second metal sheath 9 joining the tube 6 to a detonator tube 12 which is surrounded by a metal sheath 11. The fuze 3 is waterproofed and has a. textile covering and a core of pentaerythritol tetranitrate. Short rigid metal tubes 7, 8, flanged at one end, are inserted in the ends of the tube 6 to keep the bore open and assist crimping of the sheaths 1, 9. The tubes 2, 12 each contain a secondary detonating charge 24 and a primary charge 23. An open-ended flanged tube 13 containing a compressed delay composition 25, preferably a lead salt of a polynitro-phenolic compound, is held in the tube 11 by a paper tube 10 and the joints between the detonator tubes and the metal sheaths are waterproofed by thin rubber tubes 29. Protuberances 15, 18 are provided on the detonator tubes to assist in positioning the sheaths 1, 9, 11. When the assembly is to be used a length 4 of detonating fuze is inserted in the open end 14 of the sheath 11 which is then crimped to to the fuze. On initiation of the fuze 3 the charges 23, 24 in the tube 2 are detonated. The flame gases enter the tube 6, bulging it out and thereby losing some energy and pass thence to ignite the delay composition 13, which in turn ignites the charges 23, 24 and fuze 4. The fuze 4 then detonates the charge attached to it. Initiation of the fuze 3 may be by a detonator, an explosive charge or a device according to the invention. Specifications 588,613 and 638,974 are referred to.

Stropping-apparatus.-A machine for stropping safety-razor blades is constructed with two stropping-disks D, E mounted on pivoted arms B, C and driven through skew-pinions D<3>, E<3> from a shaft F. The razor blade is carried on a holder H sliding to and fro in a guide A<3> under the action of a crank-disk J. When the disks are driven for stropping, they swing on the pivoted arms B, C, and are urged towards the blade by the skew pinions before rotation of the disks begins, and on the reversal of the drive are retracted from the blade by the skew pinions; spring tongues C<3> press upon the spindles of the disks D, E, and by retarding rotation ensure that the disks move to the full limit of their swing before rotation begins, and determine the pressure of the disks upon the blade.

The wheel a is raised or lowered by means of a shaft i, which operates a shaft f through worm gear and moves the racks up and down by means of spur-wheels. The shaft of the motor is extended so as to carry the bevels m, o either of which can be clutched to the shaft so as to drive a loose bevel n. When the wheel a is down, a friction or gear wheel l engages the back of the wheel n and it is thus driven through the bevel and chain gearing. The direction of rotation is governed by a clutch operated by a lever s through a rod t.

column13: The present invention is directed to an insulin formulation comprising a suspension of Ultralente crystals and a total formulation zinc concentration of between about 0.5 milligrams to about 20 milligrams per 100 units of insulin. Greater than fifty percent of the total zinc in the formulation resides in the soluble fraction, rather than in complex with the insulin. This insulin formulation generally has a pH from between about 6.0 to about 7.4. In addition, the insulin formulation of the present invention does not contain other proteins like protamine. This zinc-modified formulation displays characteristics of a very long lasting human insulin product.
Silicone membranes and methods of manufacturing membranes are provided.

column13: The present invention discloses a generator ( 1 ) able to generate either unidirectional current or bi-directional current. A rotatable disc ( 7 ) has a conductive track ( 9 ) and a ferromagnetic bridge ( 8 ). Brushes ( 12, 13 ) switchingly open circuit a coil ( 16 ) or connect the coil ( 16 ) to a load resistor (R). Movement of the disc ( 7 ) results in bridge ( 8 ) shunting a core ( 15 ) of the coil ( 16 ). This generates an emf in the coil ( 16 ). If the circuit is closed, current flows in the resistor (R). If the circuit is open, no current flows. The arrangement is such that current only flows when the bridge ( 8 ) approaches the magnet ( 14 )-not when the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ). Thus, only the magnetic attraction for the bridge ( 8 ) by the magnet ( 14 ) impedes the movement of the disc ( 7 ) as the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ) without the disc's movement also being impeded by generation of electric current at that time.

In a door closer comprising a housing forming a reservoir for hydraulic fluid and containing a closing spring acting upon a check piston movable in a cylinder within the housing and linked with a spindle for connecting the closer to a door, a non-return valve is provided for permitting a free flow of fluid from the main portion of the reservoir into the cylinder during the opening movement of the door, and the closing movement is controlled by a pair of separate means one of which comprises a valve adjustable independently of the other means and arranged to permit a restricted flow during the whole of the closing movement and the other of which permits a restricted flow during an initial portion of the closing movement but is inoperative during the final portion of the movement. The first means is constructed so that the flow of fluid therethrough cannot be completely cut off. The drawings show a door closer adapted to be mounted in the lintel of a door frame and comprising a pair of closing springs 31 acting on pistons 20 movable in parallel cylinders 19 and linked by piston rods 40 to a pair of parallel plates 35, 36 provided with guide slots 37, 38. These slots receive corresponding shoulders 27, 28 formed on the spindle 24, and a cam 51 secured to the spindle moves in the space between the plates and co-operates with follower rollers 43, 44, 45 rotatable on shafts 48-50 mounted in the plates. Hold-open recesses 53 and hold-closed recesses 54 are formed in the cam surface. The cylinders 19 are connected by ports 80 to a bore 75 containing the first of the separate control means, which comprises a valve 70 screwed into the partition 18 between the cylinders to control the flow of fluid from the inner ends of the cylinders via a bore 79 to the main portion of the reservoir. A slight clearance between the valve stem 71 and the bore 75 prevents complete closure of the valve. The other control means comprises a tapered groove 65 in the wall of one of the cylinders which co-operates with the corresponding piston over the initial portion of the closing movement. In a modification the groove is replaced by a second valve similar to the valve 70 but spaced from the inner ends of the cylinders. A non-return valve 58 is provided in each of the pistons.

column12: Improvements relating to apparatus for supplying liquid
column13: 699,316. Filling and emptying tanks. SHELL REFINING & MARKETING CO., Ltd. June 5, 1952 [July 12, 1951], No. 16544/51. Class 21 [Also in Groups XVIII and XXVIII] In apparatus for supplying liquid under pressure from a supply source to a container (e.g. the fuel tank of an aircraft) through a pipeline system, a predetermined vacuum is maintained in an auxiliary container by an eductor connected in and operated by the flow of liquid into the main container, under control of a by-pass valve across the eductor regulated by a piston and cylinder connected to the auxiliary container vacuum, a duct connects the auxiliary vacuum container through a control valve to the pipeline system and/or the main container, and valves are provided for isolating the supply source, whereby the liquid may be withdrawn as required from the pipeline and/or main container into the auxiliary container after a supply operation, and from thence to the main line through the eductor during the next supply operation. Fig. 4 shows a fuel-dispensing system for aircraft in which reels 38, 39 mounted on a truck 37 carry hoses which are respectively coupled through automatic valves to a dispersing point 46 of a static pipe system, and to the tank of the aircraft through its internal pipework. The hoses are interconnected on the truck through a pressure control valve 41 of the kind described in Specification 668,451, [Group XXIX], a controlled eductor 1, a filter 42, and air eliminator 43, and a meter 44, while an auxiliary container 15 in which a controlled vacuum is maintained by the eductor is conneoted to the system between the filter and the air eliminator through a control valve 27A Figs. 1, 2 show the controlled eductor system, which is connected as a by-pass across a butterfly fuel valve 3 in the main fuel line tending to be closed by the liquid flow, to create a vacuum in the container 15 through a non-return valve 5 and pipe 4. The butterfly valve is controllable through a linkage 7, 8, by a springloaded piston 9 moving in a cylinder 10 so as to close the butterfly valve when atmospheric pressure prevails on both sides of the cylinder. The latter is connected through a leaking non-return valve 22 to a port 21 of the cylinder 17 of a pilot valve 13, which is also ported through a pipe 14 to the vacuum container. A spring- loaded plunger 16 within the cylinder 17 has a port 25 connected to atmosphere through a central bore 26 and a lower port 23 connected by a peripheral channel 24 to pipe 14 and through an axial channel 19 to the space within the cylinder. Initially plunger 16 is positioned so that cylinder 10 is connected to atmosphere through ports 21, 25 and valve 22. Valve 3 is closed and the pressurized fuel flow to the aircraft is diverted through eductor 1, whereby vacuum is developed in container 15. Plunger 16 rises against its spring, and at a predetermined container vacuum connects cylinder 10 to vacuum through ports 21, 23 and channel 24, and non- return valve 22, which closes but leaks so that after a time delay, the vacuum in the cylinder suffices to open valve 3 and reduce the eductor suction so as to just maintain the predetermined vacuum. On completion of the supply operation, the hoses are disconnected, whereupon their automatic valves close so that on opening valve 27A the fuel in the system is sucked back into the container 15, any fuel which has passed the motor traversing it in the reverse direction. The delivery hose may be left attached to the aircraft whereby fuel may be sucked from pipelines and/or tanks therein. During the subsequent fuelling operation, the fuel accumulated in the container 15 is drawn by the eductor into the main delivery stream. Fig. 3 shows a modified pilot valve for preventing air leaks wherein a ported airtight sleeve surrounds the springloaded plunger 16, and projects beyond the cylinder bore so as to be sealed by a resilient washer fixed to the plunger when vacuum is applied to the cylinder 17 and the plunger moves to the right. The central bore 26 venting to atmosphere is also closed by a spring-loaded valve 31, which is opened by projection 34 when atmosphere is applied to the cybinder 17 and the plunger moves to the left. The atmospheric inlet 35 has a dust filter 36.
