An immunological reagent is produced by treating an aqueous suspension of mammalian red blood cells, with a mordant, an aldehyde and a protein antigen wherein the mordant is a polyphenol or quinone of M.W. under 200. The molar ratio of mordant to aldehyde may be between 1 : 5 and 1 : 150. The cells may first treated with the mordant, next the aldehyde and then with the antigen although satisfactory results may be obtained by adding the aldehyde before the mordant or a mixture of aldehyde and mordant. It may be necessary to have a buffer present to minimise any fall of pH occuring on mixing the mordant with the aldehyde e.g. by using a phosphate buffer. The mordant may be a hydroquinone (a cross-conjugated aromatic diol capable of oxidation to quinones) e.g. toluene-2, 5 -diol, naphthalene-1, 4-and -2, 6-diols but preferable benzene-1, 4-diol. In addition the corresponding quinones and other benzene, toluene and naphthalene diols may be used. The antigens exemplified are chorionic gonadotropin (HCG), g -globulin and bovine serum albumin. The red cells used are conveniently those obtained from sheep but cells of other mammalian species including the ox, horse, rabbit and man may be used. Specific examples of process to yield HCG and g -globulin sensitized cells as in Specification 1,036,591 are given together with buffer solutions suitable for use in these processes. This reagent can be used to detect protein antigens for example in body fluids, among such antigens are chorionic gonodotropin (HCG), (HCG), serum albumin, g -globulin, insulin, tetanus toxoid and diptheria toxoid. When used to detect HCG in pregnancy urine, the reaction forms the basis of an in vitro test for pregnancy and such an application is disclosed.

column13: This invention relates to an improved golf ball holder system. The invention is used for displaying advertisements while holding golf balls. The unit is placed on a golf course or golf center including but not limited to where the golfers warm-up or practice. The unit serves a dual purpose in holding the golf balls and as a venue for advertisements to be viewed by the golfer. The unit has a section that holds golf balls along with spaces for advertisements to be displayed on the surface of the unit. The unit has indentations in the surface to enable a person to be able to change the advertising signs/plaques easily. Also, the unit has a curved slope that allows the golf balls to be easily extracted from the ball holder. The unit's face is slanted at an angle so that the advertisements can be viewed easily by the golfer.

Brass and like wind instruments.- The rim of the mouthpiece o f a wind musical instrument is preferably of oval form, and means are provided to vary the depth of the cup and the size of the throat. This barrel is formed with a number of cup bottoms 6, 6<a> and throats 7, 7<a>, and is held firmly against the body 1 by means of a rubber busbing 8, which is kept in position by means of a washer 9 and screw 10. A wind-tight joint is made at the bottom by means of a phosphor-bronze bush 11 formed with an annular shoulder 12, above which a ring 13 of rubber, leather, or cork is cemented, the whole being pressed upwards by means of a rubber band 14. The upper portion of the bush 11 fits within the barrel 4 to lock it in position, but other locking means may be provided. To enable the depth of the cup to be varied, the end of the body portion 1 is provided with a collar 18, formed with slots 22, and the rim 24 has pins 21 adapted to fit into these slots and retain the rim in different positions, as shown in Fig. 3, in which the continuous rim is replaced by a series of supporting-tongues 18<a>. The collar 18 is preferably strengthened by a ring 25, and the slots may be arranged substantially horizontally instead of vertically, a packing-ring 27 being used if necessary. Modifications are described in which springs, attached either to the rim or body, engage in notches, the depth of the cup being varied by rotating the rim until the springs are disengaged, adjusting the depth of the cup, and then re-engaging the springs. column13: This invention is a universal, cost effective, disposable, restraint strap system. A lintel, pre-fabricated from two or more elements so that it has a camber. When the lintel is in service it is subjected to both transient and permanent loads which cause it to deflect. The amount of camber is pre-set to be equal, but opposite to the amount of deflection to be expected from the permanent load. When the permanent load is applied the lintel is caused to deflect but the deflection due to the permanent load is effectively zero. Thus the lintel may be constructed from materials which have a lower modulus of elasticity than would otherwise be allowable, eg. from webs 1 and upper and lower flanges 2, 3. <IMAGE>

column13: An optical signal processing apparatus (300, 400) comprises an optical power splitter (404), such as a first free propagation region (FPR, 302), and a second free propagation region (304) interconnected by an optical grating (306) comprising a plurality (N) of waveguides. The first FPR (302) has a first optical port (308) opposed to the optical grating and the second FPR has a further plurality (N) of optical ports (310) opposed to the optical grating. The first FPR, the first optical port and the optical grating are configured to provide substantially uniform coupling of optical energy between the first optical port and the waveguides of the optical grating. A differential propagation delay (404) is provided between the first optical port and the second FPR via each waveguide of the optical grating. The differential delay (404) is substantially equal to mΔΤ, where m=1...N is a waveguide number, and ΔΤ is a predetermined time interval. The optical grating, the second FPR and the further plurality of optical ports are configured to provide a differential phase shift between each waveguide m, and each optical port n=1...N of magnitude substantially equal to 2πmn/N. The apparatus may advantageously be used to implement an all-optical discrete Fourier transform (DFT) processor.

column13: The present invention is directed to an insulin formulation comprising a suspension of Ultralente crystals and a total formulation zinc concentration of between about 0.5 milligrams to about 20 milligrams per 100 units of insulin. The bars 17, 24 lie in the same plane as they pass in contact with a gumming roller 51 and also as they rest in position opposite a reciprocating label magazine 44 where they extract a label 59. As the wheel 16 rotates, the gum bar 17 moves out of the plane of the gum bars 24, thus leaving the gummed label 59 bridging the gap between the end bars 24 which subsequently dwell in register with a pocket 11 at the delivery station. The present invention is directed to an insulin formulation comprising a suspension of Ultralente crystals and a total formulation zinc concentration of between about 0.5 milligrams to about 20 milligrams per 100 units of insulin. Greater than fifty percent of the total zinc in the formulation resides in the soluble fraction, rather than in complex with the insulin. This insulin formulation generally has a pH from between about 6.0 to about 7.4. In addition, the insulin formulation of the present invention does not contain other proteins like protamine. This zinc-modified formulation displays characteristics of a very long lasting human insulin product.

column13: A protective arrangement for an optical fiber coupler (2) includes a substantially cross-sectionally V-shaped support element (11) which bounds an open channel (12) that receives a portion of the optical fiber coupler (2). The portion received in the open channel includes jacketed regions, continuing into bare regions (22) and a coupling region (23). Respective adhesive bodies (13) secure the jacketed regions of the optical fiber coupler (2) in the open channel (12) of the V-shaped support element (11). column12: Multiple Input, Multiple Output (MIMO) Communication via Multimode Media
column13: Multiple input, multiple output (MIMO) communication systems and a method using multimode media are provided. A MIMO communication system includes an array of emitters that receives a data signal and outputs a plurality of signals (e.g., modulated light, or other signal types) representative of the data signal, a multimode medium (e.g., a multimode fiber, a fiber bundle, a bundle of cables) that receives the plurality of signals from the array of emitters and carries the plurality of signals in a plurality of modes, and an array of detectors that receives the plurality of signals carried by the multimode medium and outputs the data signal. The system can include a demultiplexer that demultiplexes a single high-speed data stream into the array of emitters as the data signal. The system can also include a multiplexer that multiplexes the data signal from the array of detectors back into the single high-speed data stream.

column13: The method and apparatus for controlling heater voltages to the heaters of a CRT includes sensing the presence of pulses at an input of the heater control circuit (800). When pulses are present (e.g., retrace pulses), or the DC is at the appropriate level, the heater control circuit reacts to provide a stable 6.3V to the cathode heaters. column12: Method of and apparatus for capturing, recording, displaying and correcting information entered on a printed form
column13: An information system for capturing, processing, and transmitting recorded information via writing devices is described. The system comprises computing devices, an application stored on a stand-alone computer or on an application server, and client devices, which execute the application as well as collect and store data. The computing device for capturing the data is preferably a digital pen. A data collector includes specifically designed forms or a graphic user interface (GUI) that enables the collection of vital information. A data storage module stores vital information processed by the application. The computing device and the client device are usable online or offline a network. The client device is selected from the group consisting of a computer, printer, scanner, or other digital devices and is usable online or offline a network.

column13: 973,620. Cigarette-making machines. MOLINS MACHINE CO. Ltd. April 18, 1963, No. 15325/63. Heading A2C. A knife-feeding device, for a cigarette machine cut-off rotatable about an axis 17 and having a sickle knife, of the kind comprising a knife clamp 24, 25 frictionally gripping the knife 20, a nut 23 engaging the knife near its inner end, a rotatable screw 27 threaded in the nut to feed the knife outwards from the axis about which the cut-off rotates and against the friction of the clamp, a ratchet wheel 32 coupled to the screw, a pawl 38 for rotating the ratchet wheel, a pawl-operating rod 35 reciprocable along the axis 17 and means arranged to reciprocate the rod at intervals to cause operation of the pawl, is provided with manual means for rotating the screw to move the nut back along the screw after the knife has been fed out to the full extent. The rod 35 is connected to one end of a lever 36, pivoted at 37, the other end of which is connected to the pawl 38. The ratchet wheel 32 is connected to a shaft 31 having a gear wheel 30 which drives a gear wheel 28 on the screw 27 via an idler gear 29. The rod 35 may be actuated intermittently either by a solenoid 33 or by mechanical means. When the knife 20 has been fed outwardly to its limit the nut 23 runs on to a plain part of reduced diameter of the screw 27 and bears against a spring 56. Return of the nut 23 when a new knife is fitted is effected by disengaging the pawl 38 and a click 42 from the wheel 32 by operating a cam 57 on a stem 58, and applying a spanner to a square on the end of the screw 27, the spring 56 urging the nut into engagement with the threads of screw 27.

column13: The present invention discloses a generator ( 1 ) able to generate either unidirectional current or bi-directional current. A rotatable disc ( 7 ) has a conductive track ( 9 ) and a ferromagnetic bridge ( 8 ). Brushes ( 12, 13 ) switchingly open circuit a coil ( 16 ) or connect the coil ( 16 ) to a load resistor (R). Movement of the disc ( 7 ) results in bridge ( 8 ) shunting a core ( 15 ) of the coil ( 16 ). This generates an emf in the coil ( 16 ). If the circuit is closed, current flows in the resistor (R). If the circuit is open, no current flows. The arrangement is such that current only flows when the bridge ( 8 ) approaches the magnet ( 14 )-not when the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ). Thus, only the magnetic attraction for the bridge ( 8 ) by the magnet ( 14 ) impedes the movement of the disc ( 7 ) as the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ) without the disc's movement also being impeded by generation of electric current at that time.

column12: METHOD OF AND CIRCUIT FOR SYNCHRONIZING DATA.
column13: Des données DS-1 asynchrones sont synchronisées au niveau des bytes et converties au format SONET VT1.5 par la mémorisation des données DS-1 dans une mémoire (20) où elles sont lues en fonction d'un signal d'horloge à intervalles (40) qui est produit par la formation d'intervalles dans un premier signal d'horloge à intervalles (48) en un rapport de 208/193 qui est le rapport entre des bits VT SPE par bloc et des bits DS-1 par trame. Le premier signal d'horloge est produit par la formation d'intervalles dans un signal d'horloge synchronisé VT1.5 (46). Une différence de fréquence entre le premier signal d'horloge à intervalles et la fréquence de données asynchrones, multipliée dans un multiplicateur de fréquence par le rapport 208/193 est surveillée par la comparaison des comptages des compteurs modulo-208 (84, 86), et, en fonction de la différence de fréquence surveillée, la formation d'intervalles dans le signal d'horloge synchrone est commandée afin d'effectuer un bourrage positif ou négatif et ainsi de compenser la différence de fréquence.

Apparatus for the vaporisation of liquids
column13: 882,878. Automatic temperature control systems. DISTILLERS CO. Ltd. March 4, 1960 [March 7, 1959], No. 7967/59. Class 38 (4). [Also in Group XXVIII] Vaporizing apparatus for a readily vaporizable liquid such as liquid carbon dioxide or liquid petroleum gases comprises a heating vessel 1 having an inlet port 2 for connection to a storage tank containing the vaporizable liquid and an outlet port 4 for connection to a gas delivery pipe 5, the heating vessel containing three heating elements 7, 8, 9 with an associated temperature responsive device 10, 11, 12 respectively, the temperature responsive devices controlling the supply to the heating elements. Whilst the vaporizer is idle, the liquid vaporizes until the liquid pressure is balanced by the gas pressure in the vessel 1. Opening of a valve 6 allows the gas to be used with a consequent further generation of gas in the vessel 1 with a concomitant drop in the temperature in the vessel. The passage of the liquid through the inlet port 2 causes a temperature responsive device to operate to close a switch 17 whereby the electric supply circuit is closed. The drop of temperature in the vessel 1 causes the temperature responsive devices 10, 11, 12 to operate in succession to close switches 13, 14, 15 respectively so that the heating elements 7, 8, 9 maintain the supply of gas. As the demand for gas diminishes, the temperature at the top of the vessel rises, whereupon the temperature responsive device 12 causes the heating element 9 to be switched off. A further reduction in demand will cause the heating element 8 to be switched off and so on. Other temperature responsive devices, to control the heating elements, may be placed in the delivery pipe 5. A fusible link 26 is provided adjacent the vessel 1 which link ruptures should the temperature of the vessel rise above a predetermined limit, whereupon a switch 25 opens to remove the electric supply from the apparatus. The heating means may be other than electric, such as for example, steam.

column12: FORMATION OF MULTI-LAYERED PAPER WEB AND DEVICE THEREFOR
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a twin wire former capable of improving characteristics for joining the surface layers of a multi-layered cardboard paper and integrating the surface layers with base-layered paper webs without using a binder. SOLUTION: This method for forming a multi-layered paper web comprises using a twin wire former 20 having a lower part wire 36 traveling between an open mesh paper forming roll 38 and a reverse rotating roll 66. An upper part wire 44 merges with the lower part wire 36 on the paper forming roll 38, and these upper and lower part wires travel through a downward bent passage as a whole, or a paper forming region. A surface layer paper web 26 is formed between the upper and lower part wires. The flow of a paper material from a head box 23, is delivered on the lower part wire 36 at the point where the lower part wire 36 is wound to the paper forming roll 38. The lower part wire 36 merges with the upper part wire 44 at a point approaching the top point of the paper forming roll 38. Since the upper surface of the paper web is dehydrated by the tension of the wires and a centrifugal force, fine fibers and fillers are not removed during the dehydration. The reverse rotating roll 66 fixes the upper surface of the paper web with a base-layered paper web 24 on a base layer wire 22.

column13: A support member is formed with a bore which receives the rotatable shaft. The sidewall of the bore is formed by a load carrying part and a shaft control part which is offset radially from the load bearing part by a shoulder. The load carrying part of the bore sidewall includes a segment which directly bears the shaft load. The control part of the bore sidewall includes a segment which is located across the bore from the segment of the load carrying part of the bore which bears the shaft load. This segment of the control part of the bearing is for restricting lateral movement of the shaft within the bearing bore so as to control the location of the shaft.

column13: 977,832. Skinning bananas. VICKERS-ARMSTRONGS (ENGINEERS) Ltd. Aug. 26, 1963 [Aug. 27, 1962], No. 32889/62. Heading A4C. [Also in Division B8] In a machine for skinning bananas, the latter are fed in succession to a cutting station 36 at which they are cut transversely into halves which are then fed endwise with the cut ends trailing to a skinning station having two gripping elements, such as rollers 44, which grip the uncut ends and draw the skin but not the fruit through a gap between the elements. Bananas from a conveyer 1 are fed via an oscillating chute 3 along inclined plates 4 and 13 to be carried and washed in a water stream from nozzles 20 and a pipe 17 between two of a plurality of guide plates 13A and to be then carried on fingers 29 upstanding from a conveyer 23 having two open-mesh belts 25 along the upper run 23B on which they are dried by a blower 31. The bananas are transferred from the end of the conveyer 23 to a first feeding means comprising a plurality of side-byside lower conveyer belts 33 carrying banana engaging lugs 34 and a corresponding series of upper conveyer belts 35. The rollers 33A, 35A carrying the belts 33, 35 and mounted respectively on common shafts but each roller 33A, 35A is independently spring urged to cater for varying thickness of bananas carried between the belts 33, 35. Between each adjacent pair of belts 33, 35 is mounted a cutter blade 36 which cuts into halves bananas fed transversely thereto. The cut halves are re-orientated through 90 degrees by diverters 37 aligned with the cutters 36 and transferred in channels defined between the diverters 37 and guide plates 38 to a second feeding means comprising a conveyer 39 formed of a plurality of spaced belts connected by groups of cross wires 43. Banana halves carried on the conveyer 39 have their skins cut longitudinally on opposite sides by knives located within the guide channels. Each banana half after being cut longitudinally is fed by the conveyer 39 to have its uncut end gripped between and drawn by one of a plurality of pairs of contra-rotating rollers 44 whereby the skin passes between the rollers 44 to be discharged on to a conveyer 45 and the fruit is squeezed out of the skin to pass through a gap between groups of wires 43 and on to a conveyer 46. Bananas inadvertently adhered to the conveyer 39 are removed from the lower arm by a stripper 47 and the lower run is cleaned by a brush 48. In an alternative arrangement the washing part of the apparatus is omitted and bananas are fed from a hopper to a separating device which delivers the bananas in spaced rows to the lower conveyer belts 33.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR IMPROVING NEIGHBOR SEARCHING PERFORMANCE
column13: In a system for mobile wireless communication, it is desirable to minimize the period of time during which the RF circuitry is powered (i.e. the RF power period). A novel method and apparatus for pilot monitoring during standby mode defers processing of pilot search results until the RF power period has passed. This approach allows more searches to be performed without extending the RF power period, thus improving idle handoff performance without reducing battery charge life.

column12: Improvements in or relating to welding electrode arrangements
column13: 915,209. Welding by pressure. GENERAL ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. May 26, 1961 [May 30, 1960], No. 19036/60. Class 83 (4). A welding electrode arrangement for tubes, rings, caps and like annular workpieces 40, Fig. 1, comprises a mandrel 1 carrying or forming a first electrode arranged to extend within the workpiece, and a second electrode 8 which is of annular form, arranged to encircle the workpiece, and have an internal work-engaging face to co-operate with the first electrode, the electrodes being rotatable one relative to the other so that during a welding operation different circumferential parts of the workpiece pass between co-operating portions of the electrodes. As described, the workpiece consists of a cap 40 which is to be welded into the end of a tube 38, the tube being clamped by a ring 31 of rubber which is disposed in a cylinder 32 and compressed on to the tube by a sleeve 33 connected to a handle 34. The sleeve 33 and cylinders 32 are connected by gears 36, a rod 27 and gears 28 to a member 25 carrying the electrode 1 and rotatable in a bush 26 by a motor 23. The second electrode 8 is secured to a bush 6 rotatably mounted in bearings 7 in a housing 5 of a welding head 2 secured to a column 3 movable vertically by hydraulic or pneumatic means to bring the internal surface of the electrode 8 into engagement with the workpiece ; the electrode is adjustable axially of the workpiece by means of a slide 21. Current is supplied to the electrode 8 from a contact 16 spring-urged into engagement with the bush 6 which is insulated from the head by insulating members 13. During welding, the motor 23 rotates the electrode 1 and the workpiece 38, the electrode 8 being pressed against the workpiece so as to rotate by frictional engagement therewith. Cooling water may be supplied to the contact 26 and electrode 8. In an alternative embodiment, the head 2, Fig. 3, for the electrode 8 is adjustable transversely of the axis of the workpiece by a slide 43 and eccentric 41, and a gauge 46 indicates the contact pressure between the electrode and the workpiece by measuring the deflection of a beam 45 on which the column 3 bears.

column13: A method for providing a cellular phone user with accurate feedback of available minutes in a service plan based on specific plan usage is disclosed. A user enters service plan information including the time period of the plan, the number of peak minutes, the number of off-peak minutes, and other features associated with the plan on his cellular phone. column13: 1296. Postans, A. J. Jan. 18. Gas and like engines.-Sparks for exploding the gases are produced by breaking a circuit of large self-induction. A revolving cam driven by the crank shaft closes a switch b, Fig. 1, in the circuit of a battery a. The wire from the battery goes to one terminal of a coil c having an iron core, while the wire from the key b goes to the plug f, which is screwed into the cylinder, and communicates with the bridge k<1> carrying one of the sparking terminals k. A metal rod h passing through an insulator inside the sparking-plug f is normally held in contact with the terminal k by springs d<1>, d<2> secured by a screw to an insulated bracket e, and communicating with the coil c by an arm d. The iron core of the coil c, when energized, attracts two counterweighted armatures l<1>, carried by an iron rod l mounted in suitable bearings. The armatures l<1> are normally held out of contact with the iron core by the action of a spring m on a suitably-formed part of the rod l. One end of a finger o pivoted in a slot in the rod l moves in a cam slot in the casing of the coil c or in an attachment. When the armatures l<1> are attracted, the finger comes in contact with an insulated collar o<1> mounted on the spindle h, and so makes a spark gap between that spindle and the terminal k. The finger o at the same time slightly rotates the spindle h, and so equalizes the wear. If the gases explode before the cam leaves the contact b the spark gap is broken by the pressure of the gases forcing the rod b outwards. Fig. 4 shows the arrangement of the battery circuit of a four-cylinder engine. Four contacts p which are successively acted on by a revolving cam are each connected to one terminal of the battery a.

column13: 783,495. Magnets. MULLARD RADIO VALVE CO., Ltd. June 11, 1954, No. 17223/54. Class 35. [Also in Group XL (a)] A method of manufacturing a magnet system consisting of two magnetic poles separated by an air gap comprises the steps of magnetizing a magnet body to saturation to provide a permanent magnet and then reducing the flux density of the magnet by 10 to 50 per cent of the value to which it drips when the magnetizing field is removed, and comprises also the step of providing the magnet body with a non-ferromagnetic sheath 4 whose thickness is greatest and least at those portions of the body which are respectively at and furthest from the gap. As shown, the system comprises two permanent magnets 1, 2 magnetically interconnected by a magnetically-soft mild-steel member 3 attached by brass bolts not shown, and the sheath may be of moulded material or a thin shell of aluminium. Adjacent the gap the magnets 1, 2 may have magnetically soft pole-pieces, not shown, whose gap defining surfaces may be parallel to each other and may be profiled. The system may provide a magnet field for a magnetron, and is stated to be concerned with protection against demagnetization such as by the inadvertant approach of magnetic objects, e.g. a tool.

column12: Sustainable green solid potassium fatty acid soaps and self thickening liquid soaps made thereof
column13: Natural green, environmentally friendly solid soap compositions and methods of manufacturing and using the same are provided with easy dispersal in water and self thickening to produce liquid soaps. The natural soap compositions contain potassium fatty acid carboxylates and preferably potassium chloride but may alternately contain potassium bromide or potassium iodide. There is a need for natural, green, environmentally friendly soaps as well as eco green packaging. Recent systems have managed eco packaging but continue to rely on synthetic non-natural fossil fuel based soaps. The inventive natural solid soaps do not require plastic or similar packaging for liquids and can be shipped as a solid bar, granules, powder, etc. and diluted very easily by the end user. Preferably the soaps are small bars that easily fit into a dispenser bottle offering versatility in concentration, lather, and thickness.

column12: Arrangement for protecting an optical fiber coupler and a method of manufacturing the same.
column13: A protective arrangement for an optical fiber coupler (2) includes a substantially cross-sectionally V-shaped support element (11) which bounds an open channel (12) that receives a portion of the optical fiber coupler (2). The portion received in the open channel includes jacketed regions, continuing into bare regions (22) and a coupling region (23). Respective adhesive bodies (13) secure the jacketed regions of the optical fiber coupler (2) in the open channel (12) of the V-shaped support element (11). A strip-shaped support element (14) is connected by respective additional bodies (15) of adhesive to the bare regions of the fiber just outside the coupling region. The support elements (11, 14) are of a material having a coefficient of thermal expansion approximating that of the material of the optical fiber coupler (2). A shrunk tubular shielding element (16) tightly surrounds the V-shaped support element (11) over most of its length and its open ends are closed by respective seals (18). Shrunk tubular bend limiters (17) surround the jacketed regions of the optical fiber coupler and pass through the respective seals (18). This sub-package (1) is so inserted into a receiving channel (31) of a housing member (3) that the open side of the open channel of the V-shaped support element (11) faces the bottom surface of the receiving channel (31). A body of encapsulating material (4) embeds the subpackage (1) and holds the same in position within the receiving channel (31).

column12: Formulação de insulina humana e processo para preparar esta formulação
column13: The present invention is directed to an insulin formulation comprising a suspension of Ultralente crystals and a total formulation zinc concentration of between about 0.5 milligrams to about 20 milligrams per 100 units of insulin. Greater than fifty percent of the total zinc in the formulation resides in the soluble fraction, rather than in complex with the insulin. column12: HYDROELECTRICITY AND COMPRESSED-AIR POWER PLANT SYSTEM
column13: A hydroelectricity and compressed-air power plant system includes a first fill pool, a plurality of internal fill tanks, an external fill tank, a wave channel, a plurality of air-generator units, a second fill pool, at least one air storage tank, and at least one generator system. The first fill pool is selectively in fluid communication with the external fill tank through the plurality of internal fill tanks while the external fill tank is selectively in fluid communication with the second fill pool through the wave channel. The second fill pool is selectively in fluid communication with the first fill pool through the at least one generator system so that a set amount of water can be circulated within the power plant system as it generates compressed-air from the plurality of air-generator units and electricity from the at least one generator system.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR CONTROLLING HEATER VOLTAGE IN CRTS
column13: The method and apparatus for controlling heater voltages to the heaters of a CRT includes sensing the presence of pulses at an input of the heater control circuit (800). In another embodiment, a DC level change is sensed at an input to the heater control circuit. When pulses are present (e.g., retrace pulses), or the DC is at the appropriate level, the heater control circuit reacts to provide a stable 6.3V to the cathode heaters. When the pulses are not present or the DC level is not appropriate, the circuit reverts to a low-conducting mode where insufficient voltage is provided to the heaters of the CRT for normal operation.

An electromagnetic force motor includes a stator having a plurality of magnets mounted along a perimeter of the rotor. Preferably, the stator magnets have opposite poles isolated from each other and pointed inward towards the rotor. The rotor will preferably have two appendages. The 1st appendage (called the major appendage for this design) will consist of a highly ferrous, magnetic material with tightly wound coils that will form a magnetic field when introduced to a magnetic field that is generated and collapsed at a frequency of from 0 to 50 khz. The 2nd appendage (called the minor appendage for this design) will consist of a highly ferrous, magnetic material, with a dimension less than or greater than but not the same as the 1st appendage with tightly wound coils numbered more than or less than but not the same as the 1st appendage. The number of appendages on the rotor may be increased or decreased as required. The number of appendages may vary from 1 to infinity. The height of the appendages is limited by the inside of the inside diameter of the motor housing chamber. The rotor will be attached to the drive shaft. The drive shaft will be constructed with non-ferrous material. The inner chamber of the motor that houses the rotor will be filled with a medium that will be used as a dielectric. This medium may vary from air to magnetic liquids. This project will use synthetic oil rated at 5W-30. This medium was chosen because the thermal rating exceeds the curie temperature of a magnet. The stator consists of low voltage high current magnetic blocks located a determined number of degrees apart from each other. These magnetic blocks will be sequenced on at a rate of 0-50 khz for this design. Higher rates may be used for future designs to increase the torque to horsepower ratio. The low voltage high current magnetic blocks will be controlled by controller digital outputs capable of sequencing on/off at a rate sufficient to satisfy the design.

Improvements in or relating to metal food and beverage containers
column13: Metal food and beverage containers are coated internally with a composition comprising a hydroxylated conjugated diolefin polymer or an ester thereof with an unsaturated fatty acid containing 12 to 24 carbon atoms or a mixed ester thereof with such acids and polybasic acids. The diolefin polymer may be derived from butadiene-isoprene, piperylene, methylpentadiene, 2,3-dimethyl butadiene or may be a butadiene styrene copolymer. The unsaturated fatty acid may be linseed, tung, oiticica, corn, castol, cottonseed, perilla or soybean oil acids, oleic, linoleic, and linolenic acids. The polybasic acids may be phthalic, isophthalic, terephthalic, adipic, citric, fumaric, glutaric, maleic, malic, naphthalic, sebacic, succinic or tartaric acid. The esters may be produced by heating the hydroxylated polymers with oils such as linseed oil at 400 DEG to 650 DEG F. or with the fatty acids, drying oils and solvent at 200 DEG to 600 DEG F. Esterification with the two types of acids may be carried out in successive stages. The compositions may include thinners, e.g. coal tar hydrocarbons, isopentane, mineral spirits, toluene, and petroleum distillates such as Stoddard solvent, and metal naphthenate driers. The diolefin polymers may be hydroxylated by reacting with hydrogen peroxide in solution in chloroform in the presence of formic acid as catalyst.

The present invention discloses a generator ( 1 ) able to generate either unidirectional current or bi-directional current. A rotatable disc ( 7 ) has a conductive track ( 9 ) and a ferromagnetic bridge ( 8 ). Brushes ( 12, 13 ) switchingly open circuit a coil ( 16 ) or connect the coil ( 16 ) to a load resistor (R). Movement of the disc ( 7 ) results in bridge ( 8 ) shunting a core ( 15 ) of the coil ( 16 ). This generates an emf in the coil ( 16 ). If the circuit is closed, current flows in the resistor (R). If the circuit is open, no current flows. The arrangement is such that current only flows when the bridge ( 8 ) approaches the magnet ( 14 )-not when the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ). Thus, only the magnetic attraction for the bridge ( 8 ) by the magnet ( 14 ) impedes the movement of the disc ( 7 ) as the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ) without the disc's movement also being impeded by generation of electric current at that time.

711,227. Fluid-pressure servomotor-control systems. SHELL REFINING & MARKETING CO., Ltd. July 18, 1952 [July 31, 1951], No. 18073/51. Class 135 A liquid dispensing system, e.g. an aircraft fuelling system, comprises a pump 1, Fig. 1, a delivery line 5 connecting the discharge s'de 4 of the pump to at least one dispensing point controlled by a valve 8 and containing a non-return valve 6 permitting flow from the pump, and a bye-pass line between the discharge and suction sides of the pump and controlled by a valve 13. This valve varies the flow through the bye-pass in accordance with the pressure at a point 11 between the valve 6 and the dispensing point or points. The pressure is that at the throat of a Venturi 7 and actuates a pilot valve member 44, Fig. 2, controlling a piston 22 connected to the bye-pass valve closure member 17. Pump discharge and suction are connected to chamber 23, 24, respectively on opposite sides of valve seat 20. With the pilot valve closed, the pressure in chamber 23 holds member 17 seated due to the piston 22 being larger than the member. When the pressure at point 11, acting on a piston 43, overcomes a spring 33 the pilot valve opens to admit pressure liquid through ports 46, 47 to the rear of piston 22 to unseat member 17. If flow through the Venturi ceases due to closure of all valves 8, the pressure becomes sufficient to move piston out of bore 39 whereupon the pressure acts on an addition piston 42 to urge the valve member 44 against stop 34 and member 17 moves to fully open position against a stop 25. Due to the additional area of piston 42, the pilot valve will not close until the pressure at point 11 drops below the initial opening pressure. On closure of the pilot valve, the liquid behind the piston 22 bleeds off through a bore 28 in the piston and member 17 to permit the member 17 to be seated. The liquid entering the chamber 35 containing piston 42 leaks away through bores 49, 50 in the member 44 and a port 45. A pressure storage vessel 14 in line 5 compensates for any leakage which may occur when all valves 8 are closed.

column13: According to one exemplary embodiment, a method for producing an up-converted and amplified transmission signal comprises performing a logarithmic transformation of an input transmission signal to form a logarithmically transformed transmission signal, adding the logarithmically transformed transmission signal to a logarithmic local oscillator signal to form a sum signal, and performing an antilogarithmic transformation of the sum signal to produce the up-converted and amplified transmission signal. In one embodiment, a log-antilog circuit for producing an up-converted and an amplified transmission signal comprises a transmission log block configured to receive an input transmission signal and to provide a logarithmically transformed transmission signal as a transmission log block output, and an antilog block coupled to the transmission log block. The antilog block is configured to receive a sum signal of the transmission log block output and a logarithmic local oscillator signal.

column12: A method for generating an electric current with an electric generator
column13: A method of generating a bidirectional and unidirectional electric current is disclosed. The method includes the steps of: (a) creating a magnetic field extending from a first magnetic pole to a second magnetic pole, (b) creating a first magnetically permeable path extending from the adjacent first magnetic pole to the adjacent second magnetic pole, (c) winding a coil about the first magnetic path, (d) connecting an electrical load across the coil, (e) connecting a switch in series with the coil, (f) enabling a second magnetically permeable path to move relative to the poles into a position between the first and second magnetic poles to shunt the first magnetic path, (g) moving the second magnetically permeable path relative to the poles out of position between the first and second magnetic poles, and (h) opening and closing the switch so that the switch is closed when the second magnetic path is moving into position and opened when the second magnetic path is moving out of position.

column12: Hour meter with incremental service indicator
column13: An hour meter having a display that provides a visual indication of a total time an engine has operated and a visual indication of engine operation time remaining in a predetermined service time interval. A plurality of segments on the display are selectively displayed in a first optical state or a second optical state. A display drive displays the segments in the first optical state at a beginning of a predetermined service interval. The drive changes the optical state of a first segment from the first optical state to the second optical state when a given portion of the predetermined service time interval has elapsed. The drive incrementally changes the state of a remainder of the plurality of segments from the first optical state to said second optical state as additional portions of the predetermined service time interval elapse to graphically display the amount of engine operation time remaining in the predetermined service time interval.

column13: A wind turbine comprises a venturi inlet 7 which focuses the wind onto a bladed rotor. The wind turbine may be mounted on a mast 8, a squat tubular under-frame base, on a flat roof of a high-rise building, or a ridge line or hip of a pitched roof. The venturi inlet 7 may comprise a truncated cone, or up to three con-axially aligned truncated cones. The venturi inlet may instead comprise a deltoid (elongated) opening (figures 4-8). When mounted on a pitched roof the venturi inlet may comprise a triangular structure (figures 10 & 11). When mounted on a squat tubular under-frame base the venturi inlet may comprise a circular arrangement split into six hexagonal cells which focus the wind towards the centre of the circle where it is deflected upwards onto the bladed rotor which has a vertical axis (figures 12-14).

column12: Flocked, foam coated, water vapour permeable, bacterial barrier - from microporous plastic film coated with foamed latex, and flocked fibres

Yarns, calendering.-To obtain a brilliant and yet permanent lustre on yarns, fabrics, &c. the material is passed while still quite wet through strongly heated rollers at such a speed that it emerges still wet. column12: Wrapped and soldered wire termination including slotted spherical terminal and method of producing same
column13: An improved electrical terminal designed to eliminate arcing and corona effects has a substantially spherical post with one or more circumferential slots perpendicular to the longitudinal axis of the terminal. The outer diameter of the wire does not extend beyond the circumference of the sphere. The number and size of the slots depends on the number and gage of the wire(s) to be connected. column12: Improvements in or relating to the manufacture of titanium, zirconium and hafnium

1,103,980. Rectifying. LTV LING ALTEC Inc. 22 Sept., 1966, No. 42415/66. Heading H2F. A rectifying circuit using controlled rectifiers such as thyristors has its output voltage maintained constant for varying input voltage by firing the controlled rectifiers at the instant when a voltage proportional to the input voltage falls below a direct reference voltage. The invention is described with reference to a three-phase thyristor bridge (Fig. 1, not shown). A first control circuit (Fig. 5, not shown) receives both phase and line voltages to obtain the voltage proportional to the input voltage for each phase. This is compared with a common reference voltage and used to fire a silicon controlled switch in the control circuit of the associated thyristor. An alternative control circuit has for each phase a Schmitt trigger (Fig. 6, not shown) which is switched by the difference of the two control voltages to give thyristor firing signals through a pulse transformer (70).

Improvements in or relating to conveyor mechanism
column13: 700,692. Endless conveyers. MASSON SEELEY & CO., Ltd. Dec. 18, 1951 [Dec. 18, 1950], No. 30821/50. Class 78 (1) [Also in Group XVI] A conveyer comprises an endless chain &c. 3 adapted to feed folded articles to a marking machine and a marking bed located over the conveyer and spaced therefrom by a distance sufficient to permit a folded article to pass thereunder whilst allowing the uppermost fold of the article to pass over the upper surface of the marking bed for co-operation with the marking means. In the machine shown for marking the foot or welt 25 of stockings folded in boxes 1 the chain 3 is mounted on a sprocket at each end, the sprocket 4 at the delivery end being driven by a motor 7 through a variable speed mechanism 8, a reduction gear 9, and a driving shaft 10, a crank 11 mounted on the latter being coupled by means of a link 12 to a rocker arm 13 pivoted to the shaft 14 carrying sprocket 4. The rocker arm 13 carries a pawl 15 which engages and imparts a step by step motion to a ratchet wheel 16 also mounted on shaft 14 and thus drives the sprocket 4. The pawl and ratchet mechanism functions as a one way drive and enables the chain to be adjusted for registration purposes. Adjustment of this step by step motion may be provided, e.g. by adjustment of the throws of the crank and/or the rocker arm. The chain is supported by guide rails 17, and provided with bifurcated projections 18 which push the trailing ends of the boxes 1. The boxes are carried in the tilted position by guide rails 19, 20. The operator unfolds the welt or foot of the stocking from the box and lays it on a supporting plate 21 disposed at one side of the conveyer. The press may be of the kind having a reciprocating head on which the die is mounted and co-operates with a pigment coated foil or other carrier disposed between the head and the work, and a platform 6 forming the lower platen of the press is arranged near the delivery end of the apparatus. The welt or foot is folded from the support plate 21 on to the platform 6 by means of a lifting plate 22, rear support plate 23 which is in alignment with platform 6, and a turnover plate 24. Progressive positions of a box are shown at 1a, 1b and 1c. The welt or foot is raised above the level of the higher side of the box 1 by the upwardly inclined lifting plate 22, and, as the box passes beneath plate 23, is turned over by the diagonally arranged plate 24 on to plate 23 so that the box 1 passes under and the welt or foot over plate 23 and platform 6. When the box emerges from platform 6 the welt 25 drops into the box into its original folded position. A guard plate 26 is placed over the conveyer in the zone adjacent the entrance to the turnover station, and the marking station is surrounded by a transparent plastic guard. A series of switches for stopping the motor are provided along the frame 2. The marking machine is preferably driven by a separate motor controlled by the conveyer drive, thus the separate motor may include a clutch operated by a cable 28 secured to a pivotally mounted lever 29 carrying a cam follower 30 which co-operates with a cam 31 mounted on the shaft 10. To adjust the mechanism the cable may be adjustably secured to the lever 29 and the cam may be adjustably secured to shaft 10, e.g. by a bolt 32 passing through an arcuate slot 33 in the cam 31 and secured to crank 11 or a flange on shaft 10. The movement of the chain is preferably such that each step brings a box to the marking station, and the conveyer drive can be adjusted to vary the rate of feed and period of dwell. Preferably the dwell period of the marking head is also adjustable.

column12: Improvements relating to Methods of Joining Metal in Lead Acid Secondary Electric Batteries
column13: 1,174,576. Welding by pressure. ELECTRIC POWER STORAGE Ltd. 22 Dec., 1966 [24 Dec., 1965], No. 54878/65. Heading B3R. [Also in Division H1] In connecting a metal terminal pillar to a plate grid formed of dispersion strengthened lead for a lead acid secondary electric battery, a joint between the grid and the pillar or between the grid and a metal member which is itself secured to the pillar is effected by cold welding. A grid 10, Fig. 1, formed by extrusion and rolling from dispersion strengthened lead has an integral lug 11 with a tapered end 13 and this end 13 is lapped over a strip of lead alloy 12 also having a tapered end 14 in a die 15. A punch 16 having a working face 17 with semicircular ends and rounded edges is applied to the ends 12, 14 at a pressure of 12,200 p.s.i. to weld them together with 50% reduction. The bulging edges of the joint may be sheared off. The strips of a number of grids are then secured to a pillar by burning. In another embodiment, a number of dispersion strengthened lead grids 20 have integral lugs 21, Fig. 3, and these lugs are arranged in grooves 22 in a lead or lead alloy pillar 23 formed with an integral terminal and the pillar is compressed in a press to cold weld the lugs in the grooves. The materials to which the dispersion strengthened lead is cold welded may be a lead alloy containing tin and selenium or tin, calcium and silver or tin and calcium or it may be pure lead.

column12: Optical scanning system for dirigible heads
column13: In a mechanism for controlling the movements of a dirigible scanning head, movement about one of three orthogonal axes is imparted to the head by means of a pair of flexible straps which are fastened to the head at opposite sides of said one axis and extend along a part-circular track at the back of the head that is centered on said one axis. The straps are wrapped around respective rollers mounted on a carrier that is itself displaceable in a direction generally along the track by a coupling to an endless flexible band driven by an electric motor-drive. The straps and the drive means for them are carried by the head for rotation with the head relatively to a support member about a second of the three axes. The straps support conductors for carrying electrical supplies to those units of the scanning head that so require.

column12: Improvements in Automatic Catchers for use with Tinning Pots
column13: 14,018. Maskrey, A. J. June 21. Tinning and similarly coating metals by dipping. -Relates to automatic machines for catching and removing the plates as they emerge from the rolls in a tinning - pot. The plate is caught by a gripper on the arm 10 which is loosely mounted on a continuously - revolving shaft 1, and is clutched thereto, as soon as a plate enters the grippers, by electromagnetic means. When the arm is moving over, it is uncoupled from the shaft and returned by frictional contact with the spring face of a drum 48, which is driven in the opposite direction to the shaft 1 by belting through the second shaft 57. The gripper, shown separately in Fig. 4, is mounted on the arm 10 at right angles as shown in Fig 1, or parallel thereto if the machine is placed at the end of the pot. The plate rises between the guides 25, 29 and strikes the switch lever 31, thereby breaking the circuit of an electromagnet 43, which liberates the pawl 15 that connects the arm 10 to the shaft. As the arm turns, a switch thereon, normally held open by an adjustable stop 66, closes and completes the circuit to the electromagnet 23, which then attracts its armature 27 on the pivoted arm 22 and grips the plate. At the end of the stroke of the arm, the same switch is opened by a second stop to release the plate, and the pawl 15 is tripped by a fixed stop to disconnect the arm from the shaft. The removal of the plate allows the switch 31 to close the circuit of the electromagnet 43 which holds the pawl during the return. The arm 10 is counterbalanced and provided with a spring-hinged joint 72 at the middle.

HUMAN INSULIN PREPARATION AND METHOD OF OBTAINING SAME
column13: The present invention is directed to an insulin formulation comprising a suspension of Ultralente crystals and a total formulation zinc concentration of between about 0.5 milligrams to about 20 milligrams per 100 units of insulin. Greater than fifty percent of the total zinc in the formulation resides in the soluble fraction, rather than in complex with the insulin. This insulin formulation generally has a pH from between about 6.0 to about 7.4. In addition, the insulin formulation of the present invention does not contain other proteins like protamine. column13: The present invention discloses a generator ( 1 ) able to generate either unidirectional current or bi-directional current. A rotatable disc ( 7 ) has a conductive track ( 9 ) and a ferromagnetic bridge ( 8 ). Brushes ( 12, 13 ) switchingly open circuit a coil ( 16 ) or connect the coil ( 16 ) to a load resistor (R). Movement of the disc ( 7 ) results in bridge ( 8 ) shunting a core ( 15 ) of the coil ( 16 ). This generates an emf in the coil ( 16 ). If the circuit is closed, current flows in the resistor (R). If the circuit is open, no current flows. The arrangement is such that current only flows when the bridge ( 8 ) approaches the magnet ( 14 )-not when the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ). Thus, only the magnetic attraction for the bridge ( 8 ) by the magnet ( 14 ) impedes the movement of the disc ( 7 ) as the bridge ( 8 ) recedes from the magnet ( 14 ) without the disc's movement also being impeded by generation of electric current at that time.

column12: Method and apparatus for inhibiting formation of solid hydrocarbon hydrates
column13: 1,056,001. Separation of liquids from hydrocarbon gas streams. REED ROLLER BIT CO. Jan. 15, 1965 No. 1999/65. Heading B1L. During the low temperature separation of liquids from a flowing hydrocarbon gas stream, the formation of solid hydrocarbon hydrates is inhibited by supplying the gas under pressure through a restricted connection to a separating vessel, and passing the expanded gas through a body of deliquescent dehydrating material to form a brine, at least a portion of the brine being directed into the restricted connection for mixing with the incoming gas stream. Make-up liquid may be added to the deliquescent material to form additional brine to increase the overall brine concentration; the supply of make-up liquid may be controlled in response to the density of the brine collected at the bottom of the separating vessel, the temperature of the expanded gas stream at its entry into the vessel or its rate of flow into the vessel. or the make-up liquid may be supplied at fixed time intervals. In the embodiment of Fig. 1, gas stream in line 37 passes into water knock-out vessel 35 and is supplied by line 34 to choke 36. (Figs. 4. 5 not shown). From choke 36 the gas enters the lower liquid section 9 of the separating vessel and passes upwards to outlet 16 through trays 11, 12, 14. tray 14 carrying solid dehydrating agent. for example CaCL 2 , NaCL, LiCL, NaOH, KOH, (Fig. 2 not shown). Brine from the lower liquid layer 18 flows to choke 36 by line 58 and pump 63 (Fig. 3 not shown). In the embodiment of Fig. 2, the separating vessel has a warming device at its lower end.

column13: According to one exemplary embodiment, a method for producing an up-converted and amplified transmission signal comprises performing a logarithmic transformation of an input transmission signal to form a logarithmically transformed transmission signal, adding the logarithmically transformed transmission signal to a logarithmic local oscillator signal to form a sum signal, and performing an antilogarithmic transformation of the sum signal to produce the up-converted and amplified transmission signal. In one embodiment, a log-antilog circuit for producing an up-converted and an amplified transmission signal comprises a transmission log block configured to receive an input transmission signal and to provide a logarithmically transformed transmission signal as a transmission log block output, and an antilog block coupled to the transmission log block. The antilog block is configured to receive a sum signal of the transmission log block output and a logarithmic local oscillator signal.

The wheels E<1>, E<2> of the chocks D<1>, D<2> run on rails c. Racks G', G<2> and pawls g<1>, g<2> carried by the chocks prevent the chocks from taking charge in either direction. The davits are braced together by an horizontal bar J carrying hooked lashings, and the sockets H passing through openings in box girders P are mounted on carriages M having wheels N running on rails n. The motion of the carriages is controlled by racks S and movable pawls s. The bar J carries a hooked thrust-bar T, which engages the gunwale of the boat and maintains the davits and chocks in proper relative position until the chocks are arrested in their outer travel. The davits are then free to overrun the chocks and carry the boat clear of the side of the ship.

column12: METHOD OF AND CIRCUIT FOR SYNCHRONIZING DATA
column13: Asynchronous DS-1 data is byte synchronized and converted to the SONET VT1.5 format by storing the DS-1 data in a store (20) from which it is read in dependence upon a gapped clock signal (40) which is produced by gapping a first gapped clock signal (48) with a ratio of 208/193, which is the ratio of VT SPE bits per frame to DS-1 bits per frame. The first gapped clock signal is produced by gapping a VT1.5 synchronous clock signal (46). A frequency difference between the first gapped clock signal and the asynchronous data rate, multiplied in a frequency multiplier (26) by the ratio of 208/193, is monitored by comparing the counts of modulo-208 counters (84, 86), and, in dependence upon the monitored frequency difference, the gapping of the synchronous clock signal is controlled to achieve positive or negative stuffing and hence to compensate for the frequency difference.

column12: Rapid, solid state reduction of oxidic ores
column13: A mixture of oxidic ore and reducing agent is charged into a rotary kiln inclined at a small angle to the horizontal, the charge travelling in counterflow to hot combustible gases while oxygen-containing gas is controllably admitted so that there is maintained at the discharge end of the kiln a temperature such that the ore is reduced to metal without fusion, while the reduction zone is progressively extended towards the charging end until maximum metallization is obtained. The rate of feed of the charge, and the kiln rotation speed, are then varied and the supply rate of oxygen-containing gas consequently adjusted to again produce a reduction zone of length such that maximum metallization is obtained. The oxygen-containing gas may be admitted by means of inlet tubes spaced along the kiln and passing through the wall thereof, while the bed may occupy 15-45% of the kiln volume. Mathematical relationships for the operating conditions relating to the two feed rates are derived.

column13: 961,544. Packaging apparatus. ROSE BROS. (GAINSBOROUGH) Ltd. April 28, 1961 [March 4, 1960], No. 7669/60. Heading B8C. A carton-closing apparatus in which cartons having end closures formed by extending flaps are fed to and through a sealing unit serving to apply gum to the engaging faces of the flaps, the flaps being then folded over and pressed on to previously folded inside flaps is provided with a series of single-flanged rollers so that the pressing operation is performed by the rollers extending over the entire width of the carton and having their flanges disposed alternately at opposite sides of the path of the cartons. Cartons 11 are fed in spaced succession along supporting rails 12 and between guides 13 by a chain conveyer 14 having spaced pushing elements 16 to a folding station comprising ploughs 17 and 18 serving to fold over the outer flaps to complete the end closure and, are then advanced through a pressing station comprising a series of rollers 19 formed intermediate their ends with flanges 21, which are disposed alternately at opposite sides of the cartons path and the rollers are rotatably mounted in a pair of supporting plates 22 and 23 secured to blocks 24 and 26 with the blocks secured to adjusting bars 27 and 28 respectively. The adjusting bars 27 and 28 are carried by brackets 29 and 31 and are mounted on sleeves 32 and 33, respectively, the sleeves being arranged to engage with an adjusting shaft 36 formed with threads of opposite hand. On rotation of a hand wheel 41 the plates 22, 23 mounting the rollers 19 are moved to cause the flanges 21 on alternate rollers to be moved axially towards or away from each other to accommodate various widths of cartons. To this end the ploughs 17 and 18 are secured to the bars 27 and 28, respectively, by brackets 42, so as to move in conjunction with the rollers 19.

The sections of the tread may be integral with the tyre, or attached thereto by vulcanizing &c.

A papermaking process includes the steps of adding to the papermaking cellulosic slurry first a high molecular weight cationic polymer and then a medium weight anionic polymer. The cationic polymer is added after the addition of filler, but before at least one of the shear stages to which the slurry is subjected prior to sheet formation and drainage. The anionic polymer is added after the shear stage which is subsequent to the addition of the cationic polymer.

column13: 1,042,069. Amplitude modulation. PYE Ltd. Sept. 15, 1964 [Oct. 3, 1963], No. 38908/63. Heading H3R. An amplitude modulator comprises a carrier signal source 1, a wave director 5 connecting the energy from the source via coaxial lines 2 to a terminating device 3 and the reflected energy from the device 3 to a load 4 and modulating means 7 for varying the impedance of the terminating device. The wave director may be a 3 port circulatory isolator and the terminating device may comprise a diode 10, the impedance of which is varied by applying the modulating voltage to its anode, connected to a shortcircuited transmission line 11, 12 which is tuned with the diode capacitance to resonate at the carrier frequency. The diode is biased so that the terminating device presents an impedance equal to the line impedance in the absence of a modulating voltage. Any non-linearity in the reflection coefficient is substantially compensated by the impedance characteristic of the diode.

The invention is a seal apparatus useful as a seal between a commode and a drain pipe comprising a pipe extension, a gasket, and a flanged base. The pipe extension comprises an extension sealing surface. The gasket comprises a sealing lip, a pipe extension clearance, and a gasket sealing surface. The flanged base comprisies a pipe bonding surface and a base sealing surface.

column13: An autogyro has rotor blades carried by a rotor head mounted on a support member (10) rotatable about a pitch axis (18) and independently rotatable about a roll axis (22) for control of the autogyro in pitch and roll respectively. The pitch and roll axes intersect one another in order to overcome the problem of rotation about one axis affecting the radius of rotation about the other axis. Means are provided to prevent rotation of the rotor head and support member about an axis orthogonal to both the pitch and roll axes.

column13: The present invention is directed to an insulin formulation comprising a suspension of Ultralente crystals and a total formulation zinc concentration of between about 0.5 milligrams to about 20 milligrams per 100 units of insulin. Greater than fifty percent of the total zinc in the formulation resides in the soluble fraction, rather than in complex with the insulin. This insulin formulation generally has a pH from between about 6.0 to about 7.4. In addition, the insulin formulation of the present invention does not contain other proteins like protamine. This zinc-modified formulation displays characteristics of a very long lasting human insulin product.

column13: A bale dispenser for dispensing hay or silage from a bale is disclosed which has a support table for receiving a bale. Drawing frame is engaged by a cable which is wound onto a winch and which in turn is driven by a motor. The cable draws the drawing frame to move a bale towards an end of the platform. Arranged at the end of the platform is cutting knife for slicing the bale and doffer elements which are rotated to break off biscuits of the hay bale as the hay bale is drawn past the knife. A storage frame is arranged adjacent to the support frame and includes a positioning frame movable from a generally horizontal position to an inclined position to roll a bale from the storage frame onto the support frame.
